t date|2020|3|31}}\n |ShortSummary    = Appa gets annoyed when he learns Umma has made plans for her life after his death. Janet  gets an internship in Africa and realizes she'll miss Gerald, who is planning his trip to Korea with Chelsea. Shannon needs a roommate and Jung thinks she wants him to move in.\n |LineColor       = A080FF\n}}\n}}\n\n==DVD releases==\n[[Entertainment One]] released the first season of ''Kim's Convenience'' on Region 1 DVD on March 7, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kim's Convenience DVD news: Announcement for Season 1|url=http://tvshowsondvd.com/news/Kims-Convenience-Season-1/22968|website=TVShowsOnDVD.com|publisher=CBS Interactive|accessdate=November 18, 2017|date=January 18, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201043535/http://tvshowsondvd.com/news/Kims-Convenience-Season-1/22968|archivedate=December 1, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; background:#fff;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=2|Season\n! rowspan=2|Episodes\n! Release Date\n|-\n! Region 1\n|-\n| 1\n| 13\n| March 7, 2017\n|-\n| 2\n| 13\n| March 6, 2018<ref>{{cite web|title=Product Details|url=https://www.amazon.ca/Kims-Convenience-Paul-Sun-Hyung-Lee/dp/B078CHZPJ3/ref=pd_sim_74_1/136-7126750-4061756?_encoding=UTF8&psc=1&refRID=07NRD3M2M5TWX2FFH7RD|website=amazon.ca|accessdate=March 16, 2018}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical response===\n[[John Doyle (critic)|John Doyle]] of ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' wrote that the show \"stays away from the pseudo-seriousness that could easily plague a comedy about immigrants and family dynamics.\" In conclusion, Doyle called it \"a clever, generally engaging screwball comedy with an eye on entertainment\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/television/john-doyle-cbcs-big-week-starts-with-the-excellent-kims-convenience/article32171547/?reqid=abbb8183-5e32-4b40-aca6-ad85df48c6b4|title=John Doyle: CBC\u2019s big week starts with the excellent Kim\u2019s Convenience|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|date=September 30, 2016|accessdate=October 5, 2016}}</ref> The ''[[Toronto Star]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s Tony Wong wrote that \"the show is good. Possibly even great. The dialogue is sharp, on point and borderline subversive. It has the potential to be a future classic. It has bite...It\u2019s funny and true, but not a reality we typically see reflected on television.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/television/2016/10/09/kims-convenience-mines-korean-grocery-store-for-laughs.html|title=Kim's Convenience mines Korean grocery store for laughs|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=October 9, 2016|accessdate=December 7, 2016}}</ref> Reviewing the series following its release for US audiences on Netflix, Bryan Washington of ''Vulture'' remarked on the series' treatment of political issues surrounding immigrants, noting the tensions are never truly in the background but also do not take precedence over the comedy, remarking \"I haven\u2019t laughed as hard all year, with feeling, as I have alongside the series.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Washington |first1=Bryan |title=If You Love Family Sitcoms, Watch Kim\u2019s Convenience |url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/08/kims-convenience-netflix-family-sitcom.html |website=Vulture |accessdate=5 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nRick Salutin, also of the ''Star'', was less enthusiastic of the show's portrayal of minorities on television saying \"only accents are funny in Kim's Convenience\" and that audiences are \"laughing at the characters not with them\". Salutin concluded by stating \"I don't see why supporting Canadian culture means you should be uncritical, as if someone will take it away if you weren't.  You should be most critical about what you care most about like public education or the CBC, you want them to be good not just there\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=u9g0F-k5CSo|title=Only accents are funny in Kim's Convenience|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=November 22, 2016}}</ref> Although not directly a response to Salutin's review, actor Paul Sun-Hyung Lee (Appa) has questioned critics' inclination to cite accents as offensive: \"They won\u2019t say\u2014but is it because you\u2019re seeing Asians on the screen? Oh, no? Well, then it must be because he sounds different. Well, guess what: Asian people have accents. The accent isn\u2019t about a joke, it\u2019s part of who that character is, but it doesn\u2019t make it intrinsically racist. If you\u2019re uncomfortable with that baggage, then you need to examine it yourself and see where it comes from.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lee |first1=Adrian |title=How to do an on-screen accent\u2014and why it can be okay |url=https://www.macleans.ca/culture/arts/how-to-do-an-on-screen-accent-and-why-it-can-be-okay/ |website=MacLean's |accessdate=24 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Mark Breslin]], founder of the Canadian comedy club chain [[Yuk Yuk's]], was critical of the show's lack of strong humour, saying \"As a sitcom, it\u2019s more sit than com. It\u2019s pleasant to watch but just not that funny. The characters aren\u2019t exaggerated enough. They lack big comic flaws. The conflicts are subtle and minor key. You want to give its creators kudos for finally putting Asians on TV in the right way, but the whole enterprise plays like a civics lesson. The characters all behave with dignity, and dignity may be the enemy of laughter.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.postcity.com/Eat-Shop-Do/Do/November-2016/CBCs-new-comedy-Kims-Convenience-is-heartwarming-but-just-not-that-funny/|title=CBC\u2019s new comedy Kim's Convenience is heartwarming but just not that funny|publisher=[[Post City Toronto]]|date=November 10, 2016|accessdate=January 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Ratings===\nMidway through its first season, ''Kim's Convenience'' was estimated by [[Numeris]] to have an average audience of 933,000 per episode, with 39% of viewers between the ages of 25 and 54.<ref name=\"season2\"/>\n\n===Awards===\nFor the [[5th Canadian Screen Awards]] in 2017, ''Kim's Convenience'' garnered 11 nominations, including Best Comedy Series, Best Actor in a Comedy Series (Lee), Best Actress in a Comedy Series (Yoon and Bang), and Best Supporting Actor in a Comedy Series (Phung).<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/canadian-screen-awards-nominations-1.3938015 \"Orphan Black, Schitt's Creek, Kim's Convenience up for Canadian Screen Awards\"]. [[CBC News]], January 17, 2017.</ref> Lee won the award for best actor in a continuing leading comedic role for his portrayal of Appa,<ref>[http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/orphan-black-star-tatiana-maslany-dominates-canadian-screen-awards-two-best-actress-wins-985464 \"'Orphan Black' Star Tatiana Maslany Dominates Canadian Screen Awards With Two Best Actress Wins\"]. ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'', March 12, 2017.</ref> and Phung won Best Supporting Actor for his portrayal of Kimchee.<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/canadian-screen-awards-creative-fiction-1.4016191 \"Canadian Screen Awards 2017: Baroness von Sketch Show, Orphan Black big winners\"]. [[CBC News]], March 8, 2017.</ref>\n\n''Kim's Convenience'' won two awards at the 2017 Toronto [[ACTRA Awards]], Outstanding Performance - Female for actress [[Jean Yoon]] and the Members\u2019 Choice Series Ensemble Award for Best Cast.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kim\u2019s Convenience scores two prizes at ACTRA Awards|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/television/kims-convenience-wins-two-actra-awards/article34144736/|website=The Globe and Mail|accessdate=28 February 2017|language=en-ca}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.actratoronto.com/performers/community/the-actra-awards-in-toronto/2017-actra-awards-in-toronto-nominees/|title=2017 ACTRA Awards in Toronto Nominees -  ACTRA Toronto|website=www.actratoronto.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170220015746/http://www.actratoronto.com/performers/community/the-actra-awards-in-toronto/2017-actra-awards-in-toronto-nominees/|archivedate=February 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe first-season episodes \"Ddong Chim\" and \"Janet\u2019s Photos\" are 2017 [[Writers Guild of Canada]]'s [[Canadian Screenwriting Awards]] finalists in the TV comedy category.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thunderbird.tv/2017/02/28/announcing-the-wgc-screenwriting-awards-finalists/|title=Thunderbird \u2014 ANNOUNCING THE WGC SCREENWRITING AWARDS FINALISTS|website=thunderbird.tv}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[6th Canadian Screen Awards]] in 2018, the series received 12 nominations. It won the awards for [[Academy of Canadian Cinema and Television Award for Best Comedy Series|Best Comedy Series]], Best Actor in a Comedy Series (Lee) and Best Supporting Actor in a Comedy Series (Phung).\n\nAs the show's third season aired in the winter of 2019 rather than the fall of 2018, it did not air inside the eligibility period for the [[7th Canadian Screen Awards]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Award !! Category !! Nominee !! Result !! Ref.\n|-\n| rowspan=15| 2017 || rowspan=2| [[ACTRA Award]]s || Outstanding Performance by a Female Actress|| [[Jean Yoon]] (\"Gay Discount\") || {{won}} ||rowspan=2|<ref>{{cite web|title=Award History|url=https://www.actratoronto.com/performers/community/the-actra-awards-in-toronto/|website=actratoronto.com|accessdate=March 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The 15th Annual ACTRA Awards in Toronto nominees|url=https://www.newswire.ca/news-releases/the-15th-annual-actra-awards-in-toronto-nominees-611074235.html|website=newswire.ca|accessdate=March 12, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble || || {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=11|[[5th Canadian Screen Awards|Canadian Screen Awards]] || Best Comedy Series ||  || {{nom}} || rowspan=11|<ref>{{cite web|title=2017 TV Nominees|url=http://www.academy.ca/category/2017-tv-nominees/|website=academy.ca|accessdate=March 12, 2018|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171104014206/http://www.academy.ca/category/2017-tv-nominees/|archivedate=November 4, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Direction in a Comedy Program or Series || [[Peter Wellington (director)|Peter Wellington]] (\"Gay Discount\") || {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2| Best Writing in a Comedy Program or Series || [[Ins Choi]], Kevin White (\"Gay Discount\") || {{nom}}\n|-\n| Garry Campbell (\"Ddong Chim\") || {{nom}}\n|- \n| rowspan=2| Best Performance by an Actress in a Continuing Leading Comedic Role || [[Jean Yoon]] || {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Andrea Bang]] || {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Performance by an Actor in a Continuing Leading Comedic Role || [[Paul Sun-Hyung Lee]] || {{won}}\n|-\n| Best Achievement in Casting || Deirdre Bowen, Millie Tom (\"Frank & Nayiyng\") || {{won}}\n|-\n| Best Performance by an Actor in a Featured Supporting Role <br /> or Guest Role in a Comedic Series || [[Andrew Phung]] (\"Janet's Photos\", \"Ddong Chim\") || {{won}}\n|-\n| Best Photography in a Comedy Program or Series || Fraser Brown (\"Frank & Nayiyng\") || {{nom}}\n|- \n| Best Picture Editing in a Comedy Program or Series || Kye Meechan (\"Gay Discount\") || {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2| [[Canadian Screenwriting Awards|WGC Screenwriting Awards]] || rowspan=2| TV Comedy || Garry Campbell (\"Ddong Chim\") || {{nom}} || rowspan=2|<ref>{{cite web|title=2017 Awards Finalists and Winners|url=http://www.wgc.ca/cscs_awards/2017_wgc_screenwriting_awards_finalists.html|website=wgc.ca|accessdate=March 12, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170730224132/http://www.wgc.ca/cscs_awards/2017_wgc_screenwriting_awards_finalists.html|archive-date=July 30, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Ins Choi]], Kevin White (\"Janet's Photos\") || {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=16| 2018 || rowspan=2| [[ACTRA Award]]s || Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor || [[Paul Sun-Hyung Lee]] (\"Hapkido\") || {{nom}} ||rowspan=2|<ref>{{cite web|title=The 2018 Winners & Nominee|url=https://www.actratoronto.com/performers/community/the-actra-awards-in-toronto/2018-nominees/|website=actratoronto.com|accessdate=March 12, 2018}}{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n|-\n| Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble || || {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=12| [[6th Canadian Screen Awards|Canadian Screen Awards]] || Best Comedy Series ||  || {{won}} || rowspan=12|<ref>{{cite web|title=2018 TV Nominees|url=https://www.academy.ca/category/2018-tv-nominees/|website=academy.ca|accessdate=March 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\u2018Maudie\u2019 Wins Big At 2018 Canadian Screen Awards|url=https://etcanada.com/news/307949/maudie-wins-big-at-2018-canadian-screen-awards/|website=etcanada.com|accessdate=March 12, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Direction, Comedy || Aleysa Young (\"Date Night\") || {{nom}}\n|- \n| Best Photography, Comedy || Fraser Brown (\"Cardboard Jung\") || {{nom}}\n|- \n| Best Picture Editing, Comedy || Aren Hansen (\"Date Night\") || {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2| Best Writing, Comedy || Anita Kapila (\"Resting Place\") || {{nom}}\n|- \n| Matt Kippen (\"Business Award\") || {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Achievement in Casting || Deidre Bowen || {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Lead Actor, Comedy || [[Paul Sun-Hyung Lee]] || {{won}}\n|- \n| Best Supporting or Guest Actor, Comedy || [[Andrew Phung]] (\"Cardboard Jung\", \"Resting Place\") || {{won}}\n|- \n| rowspan=2| Best Lead Actress, Comedy || [[Andrea Bang]] || {{nom}}\n|- \n| [[Jean Yoon]] || {{nom}}\n|- \n| Best Supporting or Guest Actress, Comedy || [[Nicole Power]] || {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2| [[WGC Screenwriting Awards]] || rowspan=2| TV Comedy || Anita Kapila (\"Resting Place\") || {{nom}} || rowspan=2|<ref>{{cite web|title=2018 Finalists|url=http://www.wgc.ca/cscs_awards/2018_finalists.html|website=wgc.ca|accessdate=March 12, 2018}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|title=The 2018 WGC Screenwriting Awards Winners|url=https://www.wgc.ca/sites/default/files/2018-11/2018WGCScreenwritingAwardsWinners.pdf|website=wgc.ca|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n|- \n| Matt Kippen (\"Business Award\") || {{nom}}\n|-\n|2019\n|[[Seoul International Drama Awards]]\n|Most Popular Foreign Drama of the Year\n|\n|{{Won}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.seouldrama.org/EN/infoCenter/InformationView.aspx?pageNo=1&idx=921|title=Seoul International Drama Awards190|website=www.seouldrama.org|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\nThese are television series with a similar premise.\n* ''[[Fresh Off the Boat]]''\n* ''[[The Family Law]]''\n* ''[[Citizen Khan]]''\n* ''[[Brown Nation]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Television|Canada}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.cbc.ca/kimsconvenience/}}\n*{{imdb title|5912064}}\n\n{{CBC Television Shows (current and upcoming)}}\n{{ACCT Best Comedy Series}}\n\n[[Category:CBC Television shows]]\n[[Category:2016 Canadian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2010s Canadian sitcoms]]\n[[Category:2020s Canadian sitcoms]]\n[[Category:Korean-Canadian culture]]\n[[Category:Fictional Canadian people of Korean descent]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Television series produced in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Television series set in shops]]\n[[Category:Television series about families]]\n[[Category:Immigration in fiction]]\n[[Category:Gemini and Canadian Screen Award for Best Comedy Series winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the play|Kim's Convenience (play)}}\n{{short description|Canadian television series}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name = Kim's Convenience\n| image = Kim's Convenience logo.svg \n| developer = [[Ins Choi]]<br />Kevin White\n| executive_producer = [[Ivan Fecan]] <br />[[Alexandra Raff\u00e9|Alexandra Raffe]] <br />[[Ins Choi]] <br />Kevin White <br />Alan Dilworth <br />Tania Senewiratne\n| producer = [[Ivan Fecan]] \n| based_on = {{based on|''[[Kim's Convenience (play)|Kim's Convenience]]''|[[Ins Choi]]}}\n| starring = {{Plainlist |\n* [[Paul Sun-Hyung Lee]]\n* [[Jean Yoon]]\n* [[Andrea Bang]]\n* [[Simu Liu]]\n* [[Andrew Phung]]\n* [[Nicole Power]]\n}}\n| country = Canada\n| num_seasons  = 4\n| num_episodes = 52\n| list_episodes = #Episodes\n\n| location = Toronto\n\n| runtime = 30 minutes\n| company = [[Thunderbird Films]]\n| network = [[CBC Television]]\n| picture_format = [[480i]] ([[SDTV]])<br />[[1080i]] ([[HDTV]])\n| first_aired = October 11, 2016 \n| last_aired = present\n| website = http://www.cbc.ca/kimsconvenience/\n}}\n'''''Kim's Convenience''''' is a Canadian television sitcom that premiered on [[CBC Television]] in October 2016. The series depicts the [[Korean Canadian]] Kim family who run a convenience store in the [[Moss Park]] neighbourhood of [[Toronto]]: parents \"Appa\" ([[Paul Sun-Hyung Lee]]) and \"Umma\" ([[Jean Yoon]]) \u2013 Korean for \"dad\" and \"mom\" \u2013 along with their daughter Janet ([[Andrea Bang]]) and estranged son Jung ([[Simu Liu]]). Additional characters include Jung's friend and co-worker Kimchee ([[Andrew Phung]]) and his manager Shannon ([[Nicole Power]]). The series is based on [[Ins Choi]]'s 2011 [[Kim's Convenience (play)|play of the same name]].\n\nThe first season was filmed from June to August 2016 at Showline Studios in Toronto. It is produced by [[Thunderbird Films]] in conjunction with Toronto's [[Soulpepper Theatre Company]], with Lee and Yoon reprising their roles from the play.<ref name=\"Nestruck\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/theatre-and-performance/torontos-soulpepper-theatre-announces-2016-spring-lineup/article27068842/|title=Toronto\u2019s Soulpepper Theatre Company announces 2016 lineup|last=Nestruck|first=J. Kelly|date=November 3, 2015|work=Globe and Mail|accessdate=November 3, 2015}}</ref>  Scripts were created by Choi and Kevin White, who had previously written for ''[[Corner Gas]]''.\n\nThe second season premiered on September 26, 2017. In July 2018, the series became available to audiences outside of Canada when it debuted internationally on [[Netflix]]. It was, however not (or no longer) available in all markets (e.g. The Netherlands) in January 2020, making the fourth season unavailable to a worldwide audience. The third season premiered on January 8, 2019 and the fourth season premiered on January 7, 2020.<ref name=\"TwitterSeason4\">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/KimsConvenience/status/1197541931179483136/video/1|title=Twitter announcement of fourth season premiere}}</ref>\n\nOn March 31, 2020, the show was announced to have been renewed for two more seasons.<ref>https://www.instagram.com/p/B-arbzfBnww/</ref>\n\n==Cast and characters==\n===Main===\n*[[Paul Sun-Hyung Lee]] as Mr. Sang-il Kim (\"Appa\"). The family patriarch, Kim Sang-il was a teacher in his homeland before immigrating to Canada with his wife where they now own and operate 'Kim's Convenience', a grocery store in Toronto's Moss Park neighbourhood. Mr. Kim is traditional, proud and stubborn, practical, opinionated and blunt. He is 56 years old at the start of the series and estranged from his son Jung, a frayed relationship he gradually attempts to mend beginning in Season 2.<ref name=\"mr kim\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/kimsconvenience/characters/appa|title=Mr. Kim (\"Appa\") - Characters - Kim's Convenience: New episodes Tuesdays|publisher=}}</ref>\n*[[Jean Yoon]] as Mrs. Kim (\"Umma\"). The family matriarch, Kim Yong-mi, 54 at the start of the series, was also a teacher in Korea. She is hardworking and kind but also meddles in the lives of her family. Her life revolves around the store, family, and church, where she volunteers.<ref name=\"mrs kim\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/kimsconvenience/characters/umma1|title=Mrs. Kim (\"Umma\") - Characters - Kim's Convenience: New episodes Tuesdays|publisher=}}</ref> \n*[[Andrea Bang]] as Janet Kim, 20 at the start of the series, Mr. and Mrs. Kim's daughter and Jung's sister. She is the family member in most frequent contact with Jung. Attending [[OCAD University]], where she studies photography, Janet is a talented artist but is frustrated by her parents' traditionalism, their lack of support for her art, and the fact that they overparent her due to Jung's estrangement from the household.<ref name=\"janet\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/kimsconvenience/characters/janet|title=Janet - Characters - Kim's Convenience: New episodes Tuesdays|publisher=}}</ref> \n*[[Simu Liu]] as Jung Kim, 24 at the start of the series. Mr. and Mrs. Kim's son and Janet's brother. Jung works at Handy Car Rental, where he is promoted to assistant manager at the beginning of the series but returns to his former job after an attempt at moving to another company is scuttled. He was a rebellious teenager who had engaged in petty street crimes, earning him a brief stint in juvenile detention, but has since cleaned up his act. He was kicked out of the family home by Mr. Kim after stealing from him and remains estranged from his father though he is still in contact with the rest of the family, and gradually reconnects with his father over the course of the series.<ref name=\"jung\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/kimsconvenience/characters/jung|title=Jung - Characters - Kim's Convenience: New episodes Tuesdays|publisher=}}</ref>\n*[[Andrew Phung]] as Arnold \"Kimchee\" Han, 25 at the start of the series. Jung's best friend, co-worker, roommate, and former partner in crime. He is promoted to assistant manager after Jung initially leaves Handy Car Rental at the end of Season 2, now serving as his superior.<ref name=\"kimchee\"> Han{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/kimsconvenience/characters/kimchee|title=Kimchee - Characters - Kim's Convenience: New episodes Tuesdays|publisher=}}</ref> \n*[[Nicole Power]] as Shannon Ross, 26. The manager of Handy Car Rental, and Jung and Kimchee's boss, she has a crush on Jung in season 1 and is often awkward in her attempts to appear cool and hip.<ref name=\"shannon\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/kimsconvenience/characters/shannon|title=Shannon - Characters - Kim's Convenience: New episodes Tuesdays|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Recurring===\n* John Ng as Mr. Chin, Mr. Kim's friend and a successful entrepreneur, owning several businesses. Fastidious, he does not like to do manual labour. He is single with a dog named Ginger. He often treats Ginger like one would treat a significant other.\n* Ben Beauchemin as Gerald Tremblay, Janet's classmate at OCAD. He is intimidated by Mr. Kim and has awkward interactions with him. He and Janet later become roommates after Janet moves out in season 2.\n*Michael Musi as Terence Pepler, a mild-mannered employee at Handy Car Rental whom Kimchee inexplicably hates. He is promoted to back manager at Handy's in Season 3.\n*Getenesh Berhe as Semira, one of Janet's OCAD photography classmates and friends.\n*[[Derek McGrath]] as Frank, a repairman and friend of Mr. Kim's who tells pointless anecdotes while working. Mr. Kim is almost always annoyed by this.\n*Soo-Ram Kim as Nayoung, Janet's cheery, popular and trendy cousin from South Korea in season 1. In season 2 she moves to Canada to attend the [[University of Waterloo]].\n*Michael Xavier as Alex Jackson, a police officer who was Jung's childhood friend and who is romantically interested in Janet.\n*[[Sabrina Grdevich]] as Ms. Murray, one of Janet's professors at OCAD. She thinks Mr. Kim is a harsh and abusive guy. Her parenting philosophy is to never say no to her 5-year-old son.\n*[[Hiro Kanagawa]] as Pastor Choi, the pastor at Mrs. Kim's church in season 1.\n*[[Amanda Brugel]] as Pastor Nina Gomez, associate pastor at Mrs. Kim's church. Becomes pastor after season 1.\n*Christina Song as Mrs. Lee, Grace Lee's mother and Mrs. Kim's friend. \n*Uni Park as Mrs. Park, a supercilious and well-to-do parishioner at Mrs. Kim's church who looks down on the Kims.\n*[[Sugith Varughese]] as Mr. Sinjay Mehta, a friend of Mr. Kim's who plays cards with him and owns an Indian restaurant. Mrs. Mehta calls him Sanjeev.\n*Rodrigo Fernandez-Stoll as Enrique, a nurse and regular customer. He considers Mr. Kim his friend, but this is unrequited.\n*Tina Jung as Jeanie Park, Mrs. Park's introverted teenage daughter.\n*Kris Hagen as Sketchy-Looking Dude, a regular customer.\n*[[Marco Grazzini]] as Alejandro, Shannon's boyfriend beginning at the end of season 1.\n*[[Ellora Patnaik]] as Mrs. Mehta, Mr. Mehta's wife and a friend of Mrs. Kim.\n*Ishan Dave as Raj Mehta, the Mehta's son and Janet's boyfriend in season 2 and her ex in season 3. \n*Gabriella Sundar Singh as Chelsea Chettiar, Gerald's girlfriend beginning in season 2. Moves in with Gerald and Janet in season 3.\n*Akosua Amo-Adem as Stacie, one of Jung's co-workers after he returns to Handy in season 3.\n*Ziad Ek as Omar, one of Jung's co-workers after he returns to Handy in season 3.\n*Lara Arabian as Mrs. Ada, a regular customer, and the matriarch of a new immigrant family. She briefly works for the Kims as a cleaner in Season 3.\n*[[Kayla Lorette]] as Dree Davis, Janet\u2019s popular classmate at OCAD. \n*[[Soma Chhaya]] as Divya, Raj\u2019s fiance in Season 3. Raj breaks off their engagement near the end of the season in the hopes of winning Janet back, whom he still has feelings for.\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Kim's convenience toronto.jpg|thumb|An existing convenience store in Toronto, Mimi's Convenience Store, at 252 Queen Street East, was redesigned to stand in for exterior shots in the show.|332x332px]]\n\n===Shooting locations===\nInterior scenes at the store, Handy Car Rental and home are shot at Showline Studios at 901 [[Lake Shore Boulevard]] East, where an exact replica of Mimi Variety, the model for the store, has been recreated. The studio is also used as the exterior of the car rental business. One episode was shot in [[Koreatown#Toronto|Koreatown]] at [[Bloor Street|Bloor]] and Christie Streets. The long established \"Mimi Variety\" store at 252 [[Queen Street (Toronto)|Queen Street East]] is used for exterior shots and as the model for the interior set built in the studio. While the signage has been adjusted, the \"Kim's Convenience\" sign uses the same red and green lettering and all other sections, such as the \"7 DAYS A WEEK\", are the original signage of Mimi Variety.<ref name=StarStore>{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/television/2016/10/09/the-real-store-that-became-kims-convenience.html |title=The real store that became Kim\u2019s Convenience |first=Tony |last=Wong |work=[[Toronto Star]] |date=2016-10-16 |accessdate=2017-12-07}}</ref> The producers also painted a mural on an exterior wall, mostly seen in the credit sequence and for stock transitional shots as well as for promotional shots. The owners of the store have retained the new signage although the business has not officially changed its name.<ref name=StarStore/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://torontoobserver.ca/2016/11/24/kims-convenience-wins-fame-for-local-store/|title=Kim's Convenience wins fame for local store|first=Yeye|last=Zhu|date=November 24, 2016|work=Toronto Observer}}</ref>\n\n==Episodes==\nOriginally set to premiere on October 4, 2016, on CBC, the series premiere was delayed to October 11, 2016, with back-to-back episodes, so it would not conflict with the [[Toronto Blue Jays]]' [[2016 American League Wild Card Game|American League Wild Card Game]].<ref name=\"Jays\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/television/2016/10/03/cbcs-kims-convenience-gives-way-to-blue-jays.html|title=CBC's Kim's Convenience gives way to Blue Jays|work=The Canadian Press|accessdate=October 5, 2016}}</ref> The first season consists of 13 half-hour episodes.<ref name=\"TV-eh\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.tv-eh.com/2016/07/12/production-on-thunderbirds-kims-convenience-begins-for-cbc/ |title=Production on Thunderbird\u2019s Kim\u2019s Convenience begins for CBC |last=David |first=Greg |publisher=TV, eh? |publication-date=July 12, 2016 |access-date=November 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nCBC announced on December 20, 2016, that it had renewed ''Kim's Convenience'' for a second season of 13 episodes.<ref name=\"season2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/mediacentre/press-release/cbc-renews-canadas-number-one-new-comedy-kims-convenience-for-a-second-seas|title=CBC Renews Canada\u2019s Number-One New Comedy - Kim\u2019s Convenience - for a Second Season|date=December 20, 2016|publisher=CBC|access-date=December 28, 2016}}</ref> Season 2 premiered on September 26, 2017.<ref name=\"season2premiere\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/kimsconvenience/blog/season-2-premiere-date-set-for-september-26|title=Season 2 premiere date set for September 26|date=August 16, 2017|publisher=CBC|access-date=August 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, 2018, the cast of ''Kim's Convenience'' took to Facebook and Twitter to announce that there would be a third season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/kimsconvenience/blog/season-3-of-kims-convenience-has-been-officially-announced|title=Season 3 of Kim\u2019s Convenience has been officially announced!|date=March 12, 2018|website=cbc.ca|accessdate=March 16, 2018|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316171311/http://www.cbc.ca/kimsconvenience/blog/season-3-of-kims-convenience-has-been-officially-announced|archivedate=March 16, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Kim's Convenience seasons 3 and 4\">{{cite web |title=Season 3 premieres winter 2019 and season 4 has been greenlit |url=http://www.cbc.ca/kimsconvenience/videos/season-3/season-3-premieres-winter-2019-and-season-4-has-been-greenlit |website=cbc.ca |accessdate=June 16, 2018}}</ref> The third season began airing on January 8, 2019.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=KimsConvenience |number=1072978014923837440 |date=December 12, 2018 |access-date=December 14, 2018 |title=\ud83d\udc47#KimsConvenience #OkSeeYou\ud83d\udc47 }}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |date=November 1, 2018 |title=CBC Announces Winter 2019 Premiere Dates |url=https://www.cbc.ca/mediacentre/press-release/cbc-announces-winter-2019-premiere-dates |location=Toronto |publisher=CBC |access-date=December 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn May 24, 2018, just 2 months after announcing the third season renewal of the show, CBC announced that the show had also been renewed for a fourth season, which premiered on January 7, 2020. <ref name=\"Kim's Convenience seasons 3 and 4\" /><ref>{{cite tweet |user=KimsConvenience |number=1214592761392971776 |date=January 7, 2020 |access-date=January 9, 2020 |title=Expect to hear these three delicious words plenty of times during tonight's SEASON 4 PREMIERE\n }}</ref>\n\n{{Series overview\n| color1     = #F7941E\n| link1      = #Season 1 (2016)\n| episodes1  = 13\n| start1     = {{Start date|2016|10|11}}\n| end1       = {{End date|2016|12|27}}\n\n| color2     = #A8BF4F\n| link2      = #Season 2 (2017)\n| episodes2  = 13\n| start2     = {{Start date|2017|9|26}}\n| end2       = {{End date|2017|12|19}}\n\n| color3     = 02A3C8\n| link3      = #Season 3 (2019)\n| episodes3  = 13\n| start3     = {{Start date|2019|1|8}}\n| end3       = {{End date|2019|4|2}}\n\n| color4     = A080FF\n| link4      = #Season 4 (2020)\n| episodes4  = 13\n| start4     = {{Start date|2020|1|7}}\n| end4       = {{end date|2020|3|31}}\n}}\n\n===Season 1 (2016)===\n{{Episode table |background=#F7941E |overall= |season= |title= |director= |writer=  |airdate= |airdateR= |viewers= |country=Canada |episodes= \n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=1\n |EpisodeNumber2=1\n |Title=Gay Discount\n |DirectedBy=Kaeden Michlick\n |WrittenBy=Ins Choi & Kevin White\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|2016|10|11}}\n |ShortSummary= After being accused of homophobia, Appa decides to offer a store discount to gay customers during [[Pride Week (Toronto)|Toronto Pride Week]] \u2014 but he doesn't seem to be very good at determining who qualifies for it. Meanwhile, Umma tries to find a \"cool Christian Korean boyfriend\" for Janet.\n |LineColor=F7941E\n |Viewers=0.835<ref name=\"premiere\">{{cite web |url=http://brioux.tv/2016/10/kims-convenience-a