0, 1994 \u2013 February 14, 1994\n* Paul F. Evans: February 14, 1994 \u2013 November 14, 2003\n* James Hussey (''Acting''): November 14, 2003 \u2013 February 19, 2004\n* [[Kathleen O'Toole]]: February 19, 2004 \u2013 May 31, 2006\n* Al Goslin (''Acting''): May 31, 2006 \u2013 December 5, 2006\n* [[Edward F. Davis III]]: December 5, 2006 \u2013 October 2013\n* [[William B. Evans]] (''Acting''): November 1, 2013 \u2013 January 9, 2014\n* William B. Evans: January 9, 2014 \u2013 August 4, 2018\n* [[William G. Gross]]: (''Acting'') August 4, 2018 \u2013 August 6, 2018\n* William G. Gross: August 6, 2018 \u2013 Present\n\n===Districts===\nThe following is a list of districts that the BPD serves:<ref name=BPDwebsite>[http://www.bpdnews.com/districts/ Boston Police Department Website], Retrieved on 2010.05.18</ref>\n\n'''District A-1''', '''District A-15'''\n:*Serves: [[Downtown Crossing|Downtown]], [[Beacon Hill, Boston|Beacon Hill]], [[Charlestown, Boston|Charlestown]] (investigations and community service), [[Chinatown, Boston|Chinatown]], [[North End, Boston|North End]], [[West End, Boston|West End]], [[Leather District]], [[Bay Village, Boston|Bay Village]], and the Downtown Waterfront.\n:*Population Served: 55,971\n:*Station Address: 40 Sudbury St., Boston, MA 02114\n:*Commanded by: Captain Kenneth Fong\n\n'''District A-7'''\n:*Serves: [[East Boston]]\n:*Population Served: 40,508\n:*Station Address: 69 Paris St., East Boston, MA 02128\n:*Commanded by: Captain Kelly J. McCormick\n\n'''District B-2'''\n:*Serves: [[Roxbury, Boston|Roxbury]]/[[Mission Hill, Boston|Mission Hill]]\n:*Population Served: 76,917\n:*Station Address: 2400 Washington St., Roxbury, MA 02119\n:*Commanded by: Captain Leighton Facey\n\n'''District B-3'''\n:*Serves: [[Mattapan]]/North Dorchester\n:*Population Served: 36,480\n:*Station Address: 1165 Blue Hill Ave., Dorchester, MA 02124\n:*Commanded by: Captain Haseeb Hosein\n\n'''District C-6'''\n:*Serves: [[South Boston]]\n:*Population Served: 35,200\n:*Station Address: 101 W. Broadway, South Boston, MA 02127\n:*Commanded by: Captain Joseph Boyle\n\n'''District C-11'''\n:*Serves: [[Dorchester, Boston|Dorchester]]\n:*Population Served: 91,982\n:*Station Address: 40 Gibson St., Dorchester, MA 02122\n:*Commanded by: Captain Steven McLaughlin\n\n'''District D-4'''\n:*Serves: [[Back Bay, Boston|Back Bay]]/[[South End, Boston|South End]]/Fenway\n:*Population Served: 77,773\n:*Station Address: 650 Harrison Ave., Boston, MA 02116\n:*Commanded by: Captain Steven Sweeney\n\n'''District D-14'''\n:*Serves: [[Allston]]/[[Brighton, Boston|Brighton]]\n:*Population Served: 74,997\n:*Station Address: 301 Washington St., Boston, MA 02135\n:*Commanded by: Captain Paul Russell\n\n'''District E-5'''\n:*Serves: [[West Roxbury]]/[[Roslindale]]\n:*Population Served: 50,983\n:*Station Address: 1708 Centre St., Boston, MA 02132\n:*Commanded by: Captain Therese Kozmiski\n\n'''District E-13'''\n:*Serves: [[Jamaica Plain]]\n:*Population Served: 37,468\n:*Station Address: 3345 Washington St., Jamaica Plain, MA 02130\n:*Commanded by: Acting Captain John Greland\n\n'''District E-18'''\n:*Serves: [[Hyde Park, Boston|Hyde Park]]\n:*Population Served: 30,631\n:*Station Address: 1249 Hyde Park Ave., Hyde Park, MA 02136\n:*Commanded by: Captain Joseph Gillespie\n\n===Divisions===\n[[Image:Boston Police Special Operations Unit.jpg|thumb|A member of the Boston Police Special Operations Unit]]\n\nThe following is a list of the divisions of the BPD:\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cityofboston.gov/police/divisions/ |title=Divisions &#124; City of Boston |publisher=Cityofboston.gov |date=2012-02-13 |accessdate=2012-02-17}}</ref>\n* Forensic Technology Division: Provides forensic services within the Boston Police Department through the following Units:\n** The Crime Laboratory Unit is part of the Forensic Technology Division. The Crime Lab provides services to the City of Boston, MBTA, and several of the colleges and universities in Boston.  This unit provides many services including: crime scene processing and evidence preservation, evidence collection, evidence & case review, analysis of evidence and reporting of results, courtroom testimony, in-service training, and various forensic lectures & presentations.\n** The Firearm Analysis Unit is part of the Forensic Technology Division. This Unit provides forensic support to the Boston Police Department, Federal Law Enforcement Agencies and area college and university police departments. This unit provides many services including: firearm and ammunition certification, comparison of ballistic evidence, crime scene processing and evidence preservation, evidence collection, evidence & case review, analysis of evidence and reporting.\n** The Latent Print Unit provides forensic support to the Boston Police Department, Federal Law Enforcement Agencies and area college and university police departments. This unit provides many services including: recovery and analysis of latent fingerprints, crime scene processing and evidence preservation, evidence collection, evidence & case review, analysis of evidence and reporting of results, courtroom testimony, in-service training, and various forensic lectures & presentations.results, courtroom testimony, in-service training, and various forensic lectures & presentations.\n* The Family Justice Division consists of the following units within the Boston Police Department:\n** Crimes Against Children Unit\n** Domestic Violence Unit\n** Human Trafficking Unit\n** Sexual Assault Unit\n* Media Relations is a part of the Office of the Police Commissioner. Media Relations provides public information to local and national media outlets, conducts news conferences and interviews, and provides Department spokespersons to ensure that the public receives timely and accurate information about department-related activities, programs, services and personnel.\n* Internal Affairs investigates incidents of alleged police misconduct; reviews complaint investigations to ensure that investigations are thorough and complete; analyzes all complaint data; and proactively assists in the development of needed training modules.\n* The Boston Police Harbor Unit, led by the [[harbormaster]], patrols the harbor daily to ensure that both commercial and recreational use of the harbor and its islands is safe. The unit also enforces maritime codes and environmental regulations as they apply to these waters.\n* The Boston Police Rescue/Recovery Dive Team has 22 members and is overseen by a sergeant.  The team is made up of various members of the department working all across the city that may be activated, as needed.  The team responds to all underwater incidents in the city or in the 42 square miles of Boston Harbor. Also, the team is the primary investigative unit for any crimes that may occur on the Harbor Islands.\n* The Boston Police Licensing Division oversees civilian firearms licensing, Rule 400 Special Police Officer Licensing, and the Hackney Carriage Unit, which is responsible for regulating all taxis, sightseeing automobiles, horse and carriages, and [[pedicab]]s in the city of Boston.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cityofboston.gov/police/hackney/ |title=Hackney Carriage Unit &#124; Boston Police &#124; City of Boston |publisher=Cityofboston.gov |accessdate=2012-02-17}}</ref>\n* [[Boston Police Special Operations Unit]] is a specialized unit within the Boston Police Department responsible for combined duties involving [[highway patrol]] and traffic enforcement, crowd control, and special weapons and tactics ([[SWAT]]) services within the city. One unique feature of the unit is that the Special Operations Unit primarily relies on the use of [[Ford Crown Victoria Police Interceptor]]s and [[Harley-Davidson]]s in their daily patrols. The use of motorcycles allows the unit to perform routine traffic enforcement; accompany parades, crowds, and visiting dignitaries; and to quickly travel to situations wherein the unit's SWAT skills are requested. Specialized trucks and support vehicles are also used to transport equipment and officers when needed. The Canine Unit, Bomb Squad, Hazardous Materials Response Unit and the Truck Team are also under the Special Operations Division.\n* The high-tech desk provides inter-divisional technical support in areas such as IT (Information Technology), Digital Forensics support, and assists in investigations of [[cybercrime]].\n* [[Boston Police Gaelic Column of Pipes & Drums]]. Founded in 1992, The Boston Police Gaelic Column is an independent, non-profit organization consisting of Boston Police officers and law enforcement officers from the greater Boston area. The Gaelic Column is affiliated with the Boston Police Department but is funded entirely through the efforts of its members and supporters. They perform at Boston Police events, parades and other events throughout the Boston area.<ref name=\"gaeliccolumn\">{{cite web | url=http://www.bostonpolicegaeliccolumn.com | title=Boston Police Gaelic Column of Pipes and Drums | accessdate=February 23, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe Boston Police Department ran a cadet program, where 18- to 24-year-olds were assigned to a division where they performed administrative tasks such as writing reports and directing traffic. After two years as cadets, they were eligible to be candidates at the Police Academy. This program was cut in 2009, due to budget cuts and was brought back in 2015. New Police cadets first started on November 14, 2016.\n\n== Equipment ==\n{{expand section|date=December 2011}}\n\n=== Transportation ===\nThe Boston Police uses the following vehicles.\n* [[Ford Explorer#Ford_Police_Interceptor_Utility|Ford Police Interceptor SUV]] \u2013 Current issue patrol car.\n* [[Chevrolet Tahoe|Chevy Tahoe PPV]] \u2013 Current issue patrol car.\n* [[Ford Crown Victoria Police Interceptor]] \u2013 Mostly phased out as of July 2019. Occasionally seen on a detail, etc.\n* [[Ford F-Series|Ford F-250]] - Prisoner Transport Vehicle (paddy wagon)\n* [[Ford Expedition]]\n* [[Harley-Davidson]]\n* [[HMMWV]]\n\n=== Weapons ===\nBoston police officers may carry \"only weapons, magazines and ammunition authorized and issued by the Department\", which \"include, but are not limited to\":<ref name=sidearms>{{cite web|url=http://www.cityofboston.gov/images_documents/rule303_tcm3-9585.pdf |title=Boston Police Department Rules and Procedures: Rule 303, Use of Deadly Force |at=Section 9, page 5 |date=11 April 2003 |publisher=Boston Police Department |accessdate=2 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120526174456/http://www.cityofboston.gov/Images_Documents/rule303_tcm3-9585.pdf |archivedate=May 26, 2012 }}</ref>\n* [[Benelli M3|Benelli M3 SBS]] (12 gauge)\n* [[Bushmaster XM-15]] ([[.223 Remington]])\n* [[Glock#40 S&W|Glock Model 22]]<ref name=sidearms/> ([[.40 S&W]])\n* [[Glock#40 S&W|Glock Model 23]]<ref name=sidearms/> (.40 S&W)\n* [[Glock#40 S&W|Glock Model 27]]<ref name=sidearms/> (.40 S&W)\n* [[SIG Sauer GSR]] in [[.45 ACP]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sites.google.com/site/worldinventory/pw_massachusetts |title=Police Weapons in the USA: Massachusetts\n |date=11 April 2003 |publisher=Boston Police Department |quote=Sigarms .45 Caliber Pistol \u2013 8 Rounds |accessdate=2 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sigsauer.com/upFiles/Specifications-Comparison.pdf |title=Pistol Specifications |at=Chart 1 |publisher=[[SIG Sauer]] |accessdate=2 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111027111717/http://www.sigsauer.com/upFiles/Specifications-Comparison.pdf |archive-date=27 October 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Community policing ==\nIn the 1990s the police department resurrected an old idea, the Walk & Talk strategy. Police officers assigned to [[police car|patrol cars]] are required to walk a particular area for up to 45 minutes or longer per their tour of duty. The establishment of other initiatives like \"Same Cop Same Neighborhood\" and \"Safe Street Beat Teams\" have contributed widely to the continued success of community policing.{{Citation needed|date=October 2009}} These types of direct patrol were more widely expanded under the leadership of Police Commissioner Davis. Under his command Patrol Supervisors and police officers who were normally assigned to administrative duties were encouraged to perform a foot patrol. This type of patrol assignment is referred to as a Code 19.{{Citation needed|date=October 2009}}\n\n== Demographics ==\n\n;By gender\n* Male: 84%\n* Female: 16%\n\n;By race\n* White: 67%\n* African-American/Black: 23%\n* Hispanic: 8%\n* Asian: 2%<ref>[http://www.ojp.usdoj.gov/bjs/pub/pdf/lemas00.pdf Law Enforcement Management and Administrative Statistics, 2000: Data for Individual State and Local Agencies with 100 or More Officers] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090802114024/http://www.ojp.usdoj.gov/bjs/pub/pdf/lemas00.pdf |date=August 2, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==Fictional portrayals==\nThe Boston Police Department has been portrayed in several prominent motion pictures including ''[[Patriots Day (film)|Patriots Day]]'', ''[[Gone Baby Gone]]'', ''[[Mystic River (film)|Mystic River]]'', ''[[The Departed]]'', ''[[Edge of Darkness (2010 film)|Edge of Darkness]]'', ''[[Blown Away (1994 film)|Blown Away]]'', ''[[The Brinks Job]]'', ''[[That's My Boy (2012 film)|That's My Boy]]'', ''[[R.I.P.D.]]'', ''[[The Heat (film)|The Heat]]'', the second \"X-Men\" film ''[[X2 (film)]]'', ''[[What's The Worst That Could Happen?]]'', ''[[The Boondock Saints]]'', ''[[Surrogates (film)|Surrogates]]'', and ''[[The Town (2010 film)|The Town]]''. BPD is also featured in the television series ''[[Spenser: For Hire]]'', ''[[Rizzoli & Isles]]'', ''[[Leverage (TV series)|Leverage]]'', ''[[Crossing Jordan]]'', ''[[Fringe (TV series)|Fringe]]'', and the failed [[Katee Sackhoff]]/[[Goran Visnjic]] police show pilot ''[[Boston's Finest (TV series)|Boston's Finest]]''.\n\n===Fictional BPD districts===\nDue to filming on location in the Boston area, fake BPD cruisers have been marked with fictional districts to avoid confusion with real BPD cruisers.  They include:\n;District A-4\n* Featured in\n** ''[[Fringe (TV series)|Fringe]]''<ref>[http://justagwailo.com/2010/10/27/10689 Photo of fake BPD cruiser on ''Fringe'' set]</ref>\n;District A-8\n* Featured in\n** ''[[That's My Boy (2012 film)|That's My Boy]]'' outside a housing project\n** ''[[The Town (2010 film)|The Town]]'' throughout the film\n** ''[[R.I.P.D.]]'' during the raid where Nick is killed\n** ''[[Ted 2]]'' seen on the side of a police car\n** ''[[Patriots Day (film)|Patriots Day]]'' outside of David Henneberry's house on April 19\n;District D-6\n* Featured in\n** ''[[The Town (2010 film)|The Town]]'' outside [[Fenway Park]] during the final gunfight scene\n;District G-4\n* Featured in\n** ''[[Patriots Day (film)|Patriots Day]]''<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://scontent-lga3-1.xx.fbcdn.net/hphotos-xpf1/v/t1.0-0/p600x600/12998763_10209781161833755_5114774848379613929_n.jpg?oh=a7477d3e10ebe31d50afbe376725a128&oe=57AFD9E0# |title=Photo of fake BPD cruiser on ''Patriots Day'' set |access-date=2016-06-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160617165922/https://scontent-lga3-1.xx.fbcdn.net/hphotos-xpf1/v/t1.0-0/p600x600/12998763_10209781161833755_5114774848379613929_n.jpg?oh=a7477d3e10ebe31d50afbe376725a128&oe=57AFD9E0 |archive-date=2016-06-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n;District G-5\n* Featured in\n** ''[[Edge of Darkness (2010 film)|Edge of Darkness]]'' outside Craven's house as part of a protection detail\n** ''[[The Heat (2013 film)|The Heat]]'' Mullins works out of it, but it is somehow part of Area F rather than Area G\n;District G-8\n* Featured in\n** ''[[Leverage (TV series)|Leverage]]''<ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/ichad/4676497363/ Photo of fake BPD cruisers with Oregon license plates]</ref>\n;19th Precinct\n* Featured in\n** ''[[What's the Worst That Could Happen?]]'' Detective Tardio claims to be from it when first introducing himself\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[List of law enforcement agencies in Massachusetts]]\n* [[Boston Police Special Operations Unit]]\n* [[Boston Marathon bombing]]\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [[Francis Russell (author)|Francis Russell]]. [https://books.google.com/books?id=GOqa9-BWvmMC&printsec=frontcover ''A City in Terror: Calvin Coolidge and the 1919 Boston Police Strike''] (Boston: Beacon Press, 1975, {{ISBN|978-0-8070-5033-0}}).\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.bpdnews.com/ Boston Police Department blog, BPDNews.com]\n* [http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/articles/2006/04/13/police_union_to_fight_merger/ Boston Globe Article on the Merger]\n* The [http://www.library.neu.edu/archives/collect/findaids/m04find.htm Police News Collection, Scrapbooks, 1961-1968] are located in the Northeastern University Libraries, Archives and Special Collections Department, Boston, MA.\n* The [http://www.library.neu.edu/archives/collect/findaids/m129find.htm Elmer V.H. Brooks papers, 1924-1998 (Bulk 1937-1968)] are located in the Northeastern University Libraries, Archives and Special Collections Department, Boston, MA.\n* [http://www.library.neu.edu/archives/collect/findaids/m124find.htm The Justice George Lewis Ruffin Society records, n.d., 1848-1853, 1885-1893, 1963-2005 (bulk 1984-2005)] are located in the Northeastern University Libraries, Archives and Special Collections Department, Boston, MA.\n* Boston Police Department Annual Reports since 1885 https://web.archive.org/web/20100613003654/http://bpl.org/online/govdocs/bpd_reports.htm\n{{Boston Police Department}}\n{{BostonMA}}\n\n[[Category:Boston Police Department| ]]\n[[Category:Government of Boston]]\n[[Category:Municipal police departments of Massachusetts]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=February 2012}}\n{{Infobox law enforcement agency\n| agencyname      = Boston Police Department\n| nativename      =\n| nativenamea     =\n| nativenamer     =\n| commonname      =\n| abbreviation    = BPD\n| fictional       =\n| patch           = Boston Police patch.jpg\n| patchcaption    =\n| logo            =\n| logocaption     =\n| badge           = MA - Boston Police Badge.png\n| badgecaption    =\n| flag            = Flag of Boston.svg{{!}}border\n| flagcaption     = Flag of the City of Boston\n| imagesize       =\n| motto           =\n| mottotranslated =\n| mission         =\n| formedyear      = 1838 (predecessor)\n| formedmonthday  =\n| preceding1      =\n| dissolved       =\n| employees       =\n| volunteers      =\n| budget          = $323 million (2016)<ref name=\"summaryb\">{{cite web|url=https://www.boston.gov/sites/default/files/fy16-volume1-summary-budget.pdf |title=Summary Budget |publisher=City of Boston |date=2016 |accessdate=2017-01-09}}</ref>\n| nongovernment   =\n| country         = United States\n| countryabbr     = U.S.\n| national        =\n| federal         =\n| international   =\n| divtype         = Commonwealth\n| divname         = Massachusetts\n| divdab          =\n| subdivtype      =\n| subdivname      =\n| subdivdab       =\n| map             = Boston ma highlight.png\n| mapcaption      =\n| sizearea        = 89.6 sq. miles\n| sizepopulation  = 617,594 (2010 census)\n| legaljuris      = [[Boston|Boston, Massachusetts]]\n| governingbody   =\n| governingbodyscnd =\n| constitution1   =\n| police          = Yes\n| local           = Yes\n| overviewtype    =\n| overviewbody    =\n| headquarters    = [[Boston|Boston, Massachusetts]]\n| hqlocmap        =\n| hqlocleft       =\n| hqloctop        =\n| hqlocmappoptitle =\n| sworntype       = Police Officer\n| sworn           = 2,144\n| unsworntype     = Civilian\n| unsworn         = 569\n| multinational   =\n| electeetype     = [[Police commissioner]]\n| minister1name   = [[William G. Gross]]\n| minister1pfo    =\n| chief1name      = Gregory Long\n| chief1position  = '''Superintendent In Chief'''\n| parentagency    =\n| child1agency    =\n| unittype        =\n| unitname        =\n| officetype      =\n| officename      =\n| provideragency  =\n| uniformedas     =\n| stationtype     =\n| facilities      =\n| airbases        =\n| lockuptype      =\n| lockups         =\n| vehicle1type    = Patrol Vehicles\n| vehicles1       = [[Ford Expedition]], [[Ford F250]]\n| vehicles2       = [[Ford Crown Victoria Police Interceptor]], [[Ford Explorer]], [[Chevrolet Caprice PPV]]\n| boat1type       =\n| boats1          =\n| aircraft1type   =\n| aircraft1       =\n| animal1type     = K-9s\n| animals1        = 33\n| animal2type     =\n| animals2        =\n| person1name     =\n| person1reason   =\n| person1type     =\n| programme1      =\n| activity1name   =\n| activitytype    =\n| anniversary1    =\n| award1          =\n| website         = {{url|https://bpdnews.com}}\n| footnotes       =\n| reference       =\n}}\n\n[[Image:BPDHeadquarters.JPG|thumb|right|Police headquarters]]\n[[File:Police Commissioner Sullivan and bishop at cardinal funeral.jpg|thumb|Police Commissioner Thomas F. Sullivan (left), 1944]]\n[[File:Boston Police (1958).jpg|thumb|right|Investigating an abandoned stolen vehicle, 1958]]\nThe '''Boston Police Department''' ('''BPD'''), dating back to 1838, holds the primary responsibility for law enforcement and investigation within the American city of [[Boston|Boston, Massachusetts]]. It is the oldest police department in the United States.<ref>http://time.com/4779112/police-history-origins/</ref><ref>http://plsonline.eku.edu/insidelook/history-policing-united-states-part-1</ref> The BPD is also the 20th largest law enforcement agency in the country and the largest in [[New England]].<ref name=brief>[http://www.cityofboston.gov/police/about/history.asp A Brief History of The B.P.D.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120304222909/http://www.cityofboston.gov/police/about/history.asp |date=2012-03-04 }} City of Boston, Police Department (accessed 3 December 2009)</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n=== Pre-incorporation (1635\u20131828) ===\nBefore the existence of a formal police department, the first night watch was established in Boston in 1635.<ref name=brief/> In 1703, pay in the sum of 35 shillings a month was set for members of the night watch. In 1796, the watch was reorganized, and the watchmen carried a badge of office, a rattle, and a six-foot pole, which was painted blue and white with a hook on one end and a bill on the other. The hook was used to grab fleeing criminals, and the rounded \"bill\" was used as a weapon. The rattle was a noise-making device used for calling for assistance.<ref>Taylor, J. [http://www.constabulary.com/mystery/rattle.htm \"The Victorian Police Rattle Mystery\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100218043036/http://www.constabulary.com/mystery/rattle.htm |date=2010-02-18 }} ''The Constabulary'' (2003)</ref><ref name=\"BPD Chronologist\">BPD Chronologist</ref>\n\nThe Day Police, which had no connection to the night watch, was organized in 1838.<ref name=brief/> The Day Police operated under the city marshal and had six appointed officers. This organization would eventually lead to the establishment of the modern-day Boston Police Department.\n\n=== Nineteenth century ===\nIn 1838, a bill passed in the General Court that allowed the city to appoint police officers, paving the way for the creation of a formal police department.<ref name=\"cityofbostonweb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cityofboston.gov/police/about/history.asp |title=A Brief History of the B.P.D. |publisher=City of Boston |work=City of Boston.gov |year=2011 |accessdate=February 26, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120304222909/http://www.cityofboston.gov/police/about/history.asp |archivedate=March 4, 2012 }}</ref> The Boston Police Department was formally founded in May 1854, at which point both the night watch and Day Police were disbanded. A fourteen-inch club replaced the old hook and bill, which had been in use for one hundred and fifty-four years. At the time of its founding, the Boston Police constituted one of the first paid, professional police services in the United States. The department was closely organized and modeled after [[Sir Robert Peel]]'s (London) [[Metropolitan Police Service]].<ref name=\"BPD Chronologist\" />\n\nOn November 3, 1851, the first Irish born Boston Police officer, Bernard \"Barney\" McGinniskin, was appointed. His presence generated considerable controversy. The ''[[Boston Pilot]]'' wrote, \"He is the first Irishman that ever carried the stick of a policeman anywhere in this country, and meetings, even [[Faneuil Hall]] meetings, have been held to protect against the appointment.\" At the time, the police salary of $2.00 a day for the morning and afternoon beat and $1.20 for the night watch was nearly twice as high as the wages of laborers. City Marshal Francis Tukey resisted mayor [[John Prescott Bigelow]]'s appointment of McGinniskin, expressing the predominant [[anti-Irish sentiment]]s in the city by arguing it was done at \"the expense of an American.\" On January 5, 1852, shortly before the newly elected mayor [[Benjamin Seaver]] (who had been supported by Tukey) took office, Tukey fired McGinniskin without giving a reason. After criticism in the press, Seaver reinstated McGinniskin, who remained in the police until the 1854 anti-Irish groundswell of the [[Know Nothing]]/American Party movement, when in the words of the ''Boston Pilot'', \"Mr. McGinniskin was discharged from the Boston Police for no other reason than he was a Catholic and born in Ireland.\" McGinniskin became a United States inspector at the customhouse and died of rheumatism on March 2, 1868.<ref>Peter F. Stevens: ''The Hidden History of the Boston Irish'' [https://books.google.com/books?id=dnudkswMjAwC&pg=PA42&lpg=PA42 p.42-45]</ref> McGinniskin is buried in the St. Augustine Cemetery in South Boston.<ref name=\"BPD Chronologist\" />\n\nOn October 18, 1857, at about 5:15&nbsp;a.m., Boston Police Officer Ezekiel W. Hodsdon was patrolling the Corner of Havre and Maverick Street in East Boston. Hodsdon attempted to arrest two suspects for a burglary. A struggle ensued, and one of the suspects was able to get behind Hodsdon and shoot him in the head.  Hodsdon died about 10:00 A.M., becoming the first Boston police officer killed in the line of duty. He was 25 years old. The murderers fled. Thousands of people visited the station house to view the body. Hodsdon left behind his wife Lydia and infant son Ezekiel who was born just 13 days prior to his death. He was buried in Woodlawn Cemetery in Everett, according to ''Boston Globe'' newspaper reports on Oct 19, 1857.<ref>[http://www.odmp.org/agency/375-boston-police-department-massachusetts The Officer Down Memorial Page]</ref> On October 18, 2007, a memorial was held in honor of Hodsdon on the Corner of Havre and Maverick Streets in East Boston.<ref name=\"BPD Chronologist\" />\n\nIn 1871, the Boston Police Relief Association was founded.<ref name=\"BPD Chronologist\" />\n\nThe Boston Police Department appointed [[Horatio J. Homer]], its first African American officer, on December 24, 1878.  He was promoted to sergeant in 1895.  Sgt. Homer retired on Jan 29, 1919 after 40 years of service. He and his wife, Lydia Spriggs Homer, are buried at Evergreen Cemetery in Brighton, MA.<ref>Information Taken from Boston Police Commissioner Order on January 29, 1919 online at the BPL.</ref> On June 26, 2010, the Boston Police Department dedicated a gravestone in honor of Sgt. Homer's service.<ref name=\"BPD Chronologist\" />\n\n===20th century===\n{{Main|Boston Police Strike}}\nOn September 9, 1919, when Police Commissioner [[Edwin Upton Curtis]] refused to allow the creation of a police union, 1,117 BPD officers went on strike. This signaled a dramatic shift in traditional labor relations and views on the part of the police, who were unhappy with stagnant wages and poor working conditions. The city soon fell into riots and public chaos as over three-fourths of the department was no longer enforcing public peace. Governor [[Calvin Coolidge]] intervened to quash further chaos. Coolidge announced that the police did not have the right to strike against the public safety and brought in the state national guard to restore order to Boston. The strike was broken, permanently, when Coolidge hired replacement police officers, many of whom were returning servicemen from [[World War I]], and the former officers were refused re-entry into the department. Ironically, the new officers hired in the wake of the strike received higher salaries, more vacation days and city-provided uniforms, the very demands the original strikers were requesting. The BPD strike set a precedent for further movements to stymie police unionization around the country.<ref name=\"BPD Chronologist\"/>\n\nCoolidge's intervention in the strike brought him national fame, which, in turn, led to his nomination as [[Warren G. Harding|Harding's]] running mate for Vice-President in the 1920 presidential election.\n\nIn 1921, Irene McAuliffe, daughter of the late Weston police chief and horse breeder Patrick McAuliffe, was among the first six female members of the Boston Police Department. An accomplished horsewoman, she was sworn in as a mounted officer of the Weston Police Department in 1913 during the town's bicentennial celebration. She joined the District of Columbia Police Department in 1920, and in 1921 she became a member of the Boston Police Department's Vice Squad.<ref name=\"BPD Chronologist\"/><ref>Boston Police Archives & Commissioner Orders</ref>\n\n====Busing crisis====\n{{Main|Boston busing crisis}}\nIn 1974 and 1975, the BPD was involved in maintaining order during the public disturbance over court-ordered [[desegregation busing|busing]], which was intended to racially desegregate Boston's public school system.<ref name=brief/><ref name=time1975>[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,917826,00.html Boston: Preparing for the Worst] Time. September 15, 1975.</ref> The protest of white citizens escalated into street battles in 1974, and in 1975 uniformed BPD officers were stationed inside [[South Boston High School]], [[Charlestown High School]] and other [[Boston public schools]].<ref name=time1975/>\n\nOn August 23, 1995, the BPD became the first police agency to send [[fingerprint]] images to the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] electronically using the newly created EFIPS (now [[IAFIS]]) system. The first set of fingerprints were for a suspect arrested for armed robbery. Within hours of the receipt of the fingerprints, the FBI determined that the suspect had a number of prior arrests, including one for assault with intent to kill.<ref>1995 Annual Report of the Attorney General of the United States: [http://justice.gov/archive/ag/annualreports/ar95/chapter2.htm Chapter II - Supporting Law Enforcement in the Community]</ref>\n\n=== 21st century ===\n\nOn December 31, 2006, 31 [[Boston Municipal Police]] Officers were allowed to transfer to the Boston Police. On January 1, 2007, the rest of the Munis were either laid off or transferred to the city's Municipal Protective Services, which provides security to the city's Property Management Department. There was no merger with the Boston Municipal Police.\n\nThe transfers of Muni's was planned in mid-2006 by Mayor [[Thomas M. Menino]].  This plan was met with heavy protest from the Boston Police Patrolmen's Association. The BPPA's argument was that the Municipal officers were not qualified to be Boston police officers due to lack of training, political patronage, nepotism and the fact that the Munis were not civil service tested.<ref>According to Pat Rose.[http://www.masscops.com/forums/showthread.php?t=21423 37 Boston Municipal Officers don't qualify for merger] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928203120/http://www.masscops.com/forums/showthread.php?t=21423 |date=September 28, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nWith the rise of the \"IT-age\" in the 21st-Century, the BPD has rose to challenge of fighting [[cybercrime]], and has a modern and competent team focusing on the increasingly complex and sophisticated methods of cybercriminals.\n\n==== 2007 Boston Bomb Scare ====\n{{Main|2007 Boston Bomb Scare}}\nOn January 31, 2007, 911 callers mistakenly identified small electronic promotions found throughout Boston and the surrounding cities of [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]] and [[Somerville, Massachusetts|Somerville]] as possible explosives.  Upon investigation by Boston Police and other agencies <ref name=\"BG\">{{cite news | author = Smalley, Suzanne |author2=Mishra, Raja | title = Froth, fear, and fury | url = http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/articles/2007/02/01/froth_fear_and_fury/ | work = [[The Boston Globe]]| date = 2007-02-01 | accessdate = 2007-02-02}}</ref> the suspicious devices turned out to be battery-powered [[LED]] placards with an image of a cartoon character called a \"[[mooninite]]\" used in a [[guerrilla marketing]] campaign for ''[[Aqua Teen Hunger Force Colon Movie Film For Theaters]],'' a film based on the animated [[television series]] ''[[Aqua Teen Hunger Force]]'' on [[Cartoon Network]]'s late-night programming block [[Adult Swim]].<ref name=\"BG\" />\n\nThe BPD's handling of this incident has been criticized by some Boston residents and justified by others:  One resident said that the police response was \"silly and insane,\" and that \"We\u2019re the laughing stock.\"<ref name=\"msnbc\">[http://www.nbcnews.com/id/16931200 Young Bostonians think city overreacted]  NBC News</ref> Another resident said that the device \"looked like a bomb. I picked it up, pulled the tape off it, and there were batteries, two on the top and three on the bottom.\"<ref name=\"BG\"/> The same devices had been distributed in nine other cities across the USA without provoking a similar reaction.<ref name=\"msnbc\"/> The [[United States Department of Homeland Security]] praised Boston authorities \"for sharing their knowledge quickly with Washington officials and the public.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,249200,00.html | work=Fox News | title=Arrest Made After 'Suspicious Packages' Paralyzed Boston as Part of Cartoon Network Marketing Campaign | date=January 31, 2007}}</ref>\n\n==== \"Occupy Boston\" Movement ====\nBeginning in September\u2013October 2011, protesters assembled in [[Dewey Square]] as a show of solidarity with the [[Occupy Wall Street]] protest in New York. The Boston Police Department handled the presence of these protesters for ten days without a single arrest, and were hailed by members of the movement for their commendable execution of their duty. In the early hours of October 11, 2011, Boston Police and Transit Police moved into the protesters' secondary camp, arresting approximately 100 protesters.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/Boston/metrodesk/2011/10/boston-mayor-says-sympathizes-with-protesters-but-they-can-tie-the-city/GFmOU1qwApiGhBNsNSzMIL/index.html |title=More than 100 arrested in Occupy Boston protests |author=Ryan, Andrew |newspaper=Boston Globe |date=11 October 2011 |accessdate=11 October 2011 |display-authors=etal |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111011171511/http://www.boston.com/Boston/metrodesk/2011/10/boston-mayor-says-sympathizes-with-protesters-but-they-can-tie-the-city/GFmOU1qwApiGhBNsNSzMIL/index.html |archivedate=October 11, 2011 }}</ref> Protesters claimed there were incidents of excessive force by police, however, Mayor Menino denied the claim, explaining that the occupation's move into another section of the Greenway endangered public safety.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boston.cbslocal.com/2011/10/11/menino-disputes-police-brutality-claims-in-occupy-boston-arrests/ |title=Menino Disputes Police Brutality Claims In \u2018Occupy Boston\u2019 Arrests \u00ab CBS Boston |publisher=Boston.cbslocal.com |date=2011-10-11 |accessdate=2012-02-17}}</ref>\n\n==Departmental organization==\n{{More citations needed section|date=August 2009}}\n[[Image:Boston Police - Special Operations Officer.jpg|thumb|A Boston Police Special Operations officer]]\n[[File:Boston Police cruiser on Beacon Street.jpg|thumb|A Boston Police cruiser on Beacon Street]]\n[[Image:BostonPoliceKiosk.jpg|thumb|upright|Boston Police Department [[kiosk]] in [[Downtown Crossing]]]]\n\nThe Boston Police Department has approximately 2,015 officers and 808 civilian personnel, with patrol services covering an area of 89.6&nbsp;mi<sup>2</sup> (232.1&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>) and a population of 617,594. The BPD requires all employed officers hired since 1995 to live within Boston city-limits, and this has led to calls for pay raises to help officers meet the city's high cost of living.{{Citation needed|date=June 2009}} The BPD is divided into three zones and 11 neighborhood districts spread across the city, with each zone supervised by a Deputy Superintendent and every district headed by a Captain.<ref name=\"BPD Chronologist\"/>\n\nThe Boston Police Department is organized into bureaus under the Office of the Police Commissioner. The Chief of Staff, media liaisons and the Boston Regional Intelligence Center (BRIC) also operate out of the Commissioner's office.<ref>Boston Police Web page</ref>\n\nThe Bureau of Field Services (BFS) consists of the zone commands and police districts, the Special Operations Unit and Youth Violence Strike Force (gang unit). It is the largest bureau and its main responsibility is tactical patrol and crime prevention.\n\nThe Bureau of Investigative Services (BIS) consists of the Homicide Unit, Drug Control Unit, Family Justice Center and Forensic Science Division. Superintendent Kevin Buckley is the head of the BIS.\n\nOther bureaus include the Bureau of Administration & Technology and the Bureau of Professional Standards and Development, which encompasses the Training and Education Division, Internal Affairs and Anti-Corruption, headed by Superintendent Frank Mancini.\n\n=== Ranks ===\nThe Boston Police rank structure is as follows:\n{| cellspacing=\"5\" cellpadding=\"5\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Title\n!Insignia\n!Notes\n|-\n|Commissioner (civilian)\n|\n|Appointed by the Mayor of Boston. Is the Executive Head of the department.\n|-\n|Superintendent In Chief\n|[[File:New York Fire Department Chief Rank.png|center|80px]]\n|Highest-ranking police officer in the department. This position is not always filled.\n|-\n|Superintendent\n|[[File:4 Gold Stars.svg|center|108px]]\n|Superintendents are typically in charge of a Bureau, or they can be  the director of the academy\n|-\n|Deputy Superintendent\n|[[File:3 Gold Stars.svg|center|81px]]\n|Deputy Superintendents are typically second-in-command of a Bureau, or the deputy director of the academy\n|-\n|Captain/Captain Detective\n|[[File:Captain insignia gold.svg|center|25px]]\n|Captains are typically commanders in charge of a district, or unit commander in academy, or service chief in the department administration\n|-\n|Lieutenant/Lieutenant Detective\n|[[File:US-OF1B.svg|center|10px]]\n|Lieutenants are holding the functions of  second-in-command the district, or Unit leader in district, or service chief in the department administration, or instructor in academy\n|-\n|Sergeant/Sergeant Detective\n|[[File:U.S. police sergeant yellow rank chevrons.svg|center|40px]]\n|Sergeants are holding a functions of district sergeant, or unit deputy chief in district or staff sergeant  in the department administration, or instructor in academy\n|-\n|Detective\n|Detective is a rank, guaranteed by a Legislative Act of 1986, they work in civil clothes and hold the function of an investigator.\n|-\n|Police Officer\n|Police Officers are the first ranking officers.\n|-\n|* Certain jobs within the department are designated as Detective Supervisor jobs (District Det. Supervisor, Sexual Assault Unit, Domestic Violence, etc.), then, Detective Supervisors earn their \"rating\" after serving a certain amount of time in said role.\n|* Deputy Superintendents and above serve at the pleasure of the Police Commissioner and in the case of the Commissioner, the Mayor.\n|-\n|}\n\nThe Superintendent In Chief is Gregory P. Long.<ref>[https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2014/01/08/superintendent-william-gross-named-commander-boston-police/Logq4DM8XtltWtRK8GRz6J/story.html Superintendent William Gross to be named No. 2 commander of Boston police \u2013 ''The Boston Globe''<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nBoston's former Police Commissioner [[Kathleen O'Toole]] was the first woman to serve in that position, until she resigned from her commissionership on June 30, 2006, to take a new position as Chief Inspector of the Inspectorate of the Irish national police force, the [[Garda S\u00edoch\u00e1na]]. Upon her departure, Albert Goslin was appointed acting commissioner.\n\n=== Leadership ===\nThe Boston Police Commissioner is [[William G. Gross]].\n\n====Members of the Boston Police Commission====\n* [[Henry S. Russell]]: July 8, 1878 March 1, 1880\n* [[Samual R. Spinney]]: July 8, 1878 May 3, 1880\n* [[James M. Bugbee]]: July 8, 1878 May 5, 1879\n* Henry Walker: May 5, 1879 April 21, 1882\n* [[Edward J. Jones]]: March 26, 1880 April 21, 1882\n* [[Thomas J. Gargan]]: May 3, 1880 April 21, 1882\n* [[Thomas L. Jerks]]: April 22, 1882 July 23, 1885\n* [[Nathaniel Wales]]: April 22, 1882 July 7, 1885\n* [[Benjamin D. Barley]]: April 22, 1882 May 6, 1883\n* [[Michael P. Curran]]: May 7, 1883 July 23, 1885\n* [[Albert T. Whiting]]: July 2, 1885 May 6, 1895\n* [[William H. Lee (police commissioner)|William H. Lee]]: July 23, 1885 May 28, 1894\n* [[William M. Osborne]]: July 23, 1885 April 30, 1893\n* [[Robert F. Clark]]: May 1, 1893 May 4, 1903\n* [[Augustus P. Martin]]: May 28, 1894 May 1, 1899\n* [[Charles P. Curtis, Jr]]:May 6, 1895 May 1, 1905\n* [[Harry F. Adams]]: May 1, 1899 June 4, 1906\n* [[William H. Emmons]]: 1903\u20131906\n\n==== List of Boston Police Commissioners ====\n* [[Stephen O'Meara]]: June 4, 1906 \u2013 December 14, 1918\n* Michael H. Crowley (''Acting''): December 14, 1918 \u2013 December 30, 1918\n* [[Edwin Upton Curtis]]: December 30, 1918 \u2013 March 28, 1922\n* Michael H. Crowley (''Acting''): March 28, 1922 \u2013 April 3, 1922\n* [[Herbert A. Wilson]]: April 3, 1922 \u2013 May 5, 1930\n* Michael H. Crowley (''Acting''): May 5, 1930 \u2013 May 8, 1930\n* [[Eugene Hultman]]: May 8, 1930 \u2013 December 27, 1934\n* [[Joseph J. Leonard]]: December 27, 1934 \u2013 February 23, 1935\n* [[Eugene M. McSweeney]]: February 23, 1935 \u2013 November 25, 1936\n* [[Joseph F. Timilty (police commissioner)|Joseph F. Timilty]]: November 25, 1936 \u2013 March 27, 1943\n* Thomas S. J. Kavanagh (''Acting''): March 27, 1943 \u2013 June 5, 1943\n* [[Joseph F. Timilty (police commissioner)|Joseph F. Timilty]]: June 5, 1943 \u2013 November 25, 1943\n* [[Thomas F. Sullivan]]: November 26, 1943 \u2013 August 27, 1957\n* James F. Daley (''Acting''): August 27, 1957 \u2013 September 4, 1957\n* [[Leo J. Sullivan]]: September 4, 1957 \u2013 March 15, 1962\n* Francis J. Hennessy (''Acting''): March 15, 1962 \u2013 April 6, 1962\n* [[Edmund McNamara|Edmund L. McNamara]]: April 6, 1962 \u2013 May 31, 1972\n* William J. Taylor (''Acting''): May 31, 1972 \u2013 November 1, 1972\n* Robert J. diGrazia: November 1, 1972 \u2013 November 15, 1976\n* [[Joseph M. Jordan]]: November 15, 1976 \u2013 January 31, 1985\n* [[Francis Roache]] (''Acting''): February 1, 1985 \u2013 March 13, 1985\n* Francis Roache: March 13, 1985 \u2013 June 30, 1993\n* [[William J. Bratton]]: June 30, 1993 \u2013 January 10, 1994\n* [[Paul F. Evans]] (''Acting''): January 10, 1994 \u2013 February 14, 1994\n* Paul F. Evans: February 14, 1994 \u2013 November 14, 2003\n* James Hussey (''Acting''): November 14, 2003 \u2013 February 19, 2004\n* [[Kathleen O'Toole]]: February 19, 2004 \u2013 May 31, 2006\n* Al Goslin (''Acting''): May 31, 2006 \u2013 December 5, 2006\n* [[Edward F. Davis III]]: December 5, 2006 \u2013 October 2013\n* [[William B. Evans]] (''Acting''): November 1, 2013 \u2013 January 9, 2014\n* William B. Evans: January 9, 2014 \u2013 August 4, 2018\n* [[William G. Gross]]: (''Acting'') August 4, 2018 \u2013 August 6, 2018\n* William G. Gross: August 6, 2018 \u2013 Present\n\n===Districts===\nThe following is a list of districts that the BPD serves:<ref name=BPDwebsite>[http://www.bpdnews.com/districts/ Boston Police Department Website], Retrieved on 2010.05.18</ref>\n\n'''District A-1''', '''District A-15'''\n:*Serves: [[Downtown Crossing|Downtown]], [[Beacon Hill, Boston|Beacon Hill]], [[Charlestown, Boston|Charlestown]] (investigations and community service), [[Chinatown, Boston|Chinatown]], [[North End, Boston|North End]], [[West End, Boston|West End]], [[Leather District]], [[Bay Village, Boston|Bay Village]], and the Downtown Waterfront.\n:*Population Served: 55,971\n:*Station Address: 40 Sudbury St., Boston, MA 02114\n:*Commanded by: Captain Kenneth Fong\n\n'''District A-7'''\n:*Serves: [[East Boston]]\n:*Population Served: 40,508\n:*Station Address: 69 Paris St., East Boston, MA 02128\n:*Commanded by: Captain Kelly J. McCormick\n\n'''District B-2'''\n:*Serves: [[Roxbury, Boston|Roxbury]]/[[Mission Hill, Boston|Mission Hill]]\n:*Population Served: 76,917\n:*Station Address: 2400 Washington St., Roxbury, MA 02119\n:*Commanded by: Captain Leighton Facey\n\n'''District B-3'''\n:*Serves: [[Mattapan]]/North Dorchester\n:*Population Served: 36,480\n:*Station Address: 1165 Blue Hill Ave., Dorchester, MA 02124\n:*Commanded by: Captain Haseeb Hosein\n\n'''District C-6'''\n:*Serves: [[South Boston]]\n:*Population Served: 35,200\n:*Station Address: 101 W. Broadway, South Boston, MA 02127\n:*Commanded by: Captain Joseph Boyle\n\n'''District C-11'''\n:*Serves: [[Dorchester, Boston|Dorchester]]\n:*Population Served: 91,982\n:*Station Address: 40 Gibson St., Dorchester, MA 02122\n:*Commanded by: Captain Steven McLaughlin\n\n'''District D-4'''\n:*Serves: [[Back Bay, Boston|Back Bay]]/[[South End, Boston|South End]]/Fenway\n:*Population Served: 77,773\n:*Station Address: 650 Harrison Ave., Boston, MA 02116\n:*Commanded by: Captain Steven Sweeney\n\n'''District D-14'''\n:*Serves: [[Allston]]/[[Brighton, Boston|Brighton]]\n:*Population Served: 74,997\n:*Station Address: 301 Washington St., Boston, MA 02135\n:*Commanded by: Captain Paul Russell\n\n'''District E-5'''\n:*Serves: [[West Roxbury]]/[[Roslindale]]\n:*Population Served: 50,983\n:*Station Address: 1708 Centre St., Boston, MA 02132\n:*Commanded by: Captain Therese Kozmiski\n\n'''District E-13'''\n:*Serves: [[Jamaica Plain]]\n:*Population Served: 37,468\n:*Station Address: 3345 Washington St., Jamaica Plain, MA 02130\n:*Commanded by: Acting Captain John Greland\n\n'''District E-18'''\n:*Serves: [[Hyde Park, Boston|Hyde Park]]\n:*Population Served: 30,631\n:*Station Address: 1249 Hyde Park Ave., Hyde Park, MA 02136\n:*Commanded by: Captain Joseph Gillespie\n\n===Divisions===\n[[Image:Boston Police Special Operations Unit.jpg|thumb|A member of the Boston Police Special Operations Unit]]\n\nThe following is a list of the divisions of the BPD:\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cityofboston.gov/police/divisions/ |title=Divisions &#124; City of Boston |publisher=Cityofboston.gov |date=2012-02-13 |accessdate=2012-02-17}}</ref>\n* Forensic Technology Division: Provides forensic services within the Boston Police Department through the following Units:\n** The Crime Laboratory Unit is part of the Forensic Technology Division. The Crime Lab provides services to the City of Boston, MBTA, and several of the colleges and universities in Boston.  This unit provides many services including: crime scene processing and evidence preservation, evidence collection, evidence & case review, analysis of evidence and reporting of results, courtroom testimony, in-service training, and various forensic lectures & presentations.\n** The Firearm Analysis Unit is part of the Forensic Technology Division. This Unit provides forensic support to the Boston Police Department, Federal Law Enforcement Agencies and area college and university police departments. This unit provides many services including: firearm and ammunition certification, comparison of ballistic evidence, crime scene processing and evidence preservation, evidence collection, evidence & case review, analysis of evidence and reporting.\n** The Latent Print Unit provides forensic support to the Boston Police Department, Federal Law Enforcement Agencies and area college and university police departments. This unit provides many services including: recovery and analysis of latent fingerprints, crime scene processing and evidence preservation, evidence collection, evidence & case review, analysis of evidence and reporting of results, courtroom testimony, in-service training, and various forensic lectures & presentations.results, courtroom testimony, in-service training, and various forensic lectures & presentations.\n* The Family Justice Division consists of the following units within the Boston Police Department:\n** Crimes Against Children Unit\n** Domestic Violence Unit\n** Human Trafficking Unit\n** Sexual Assault Unit\n* Media Relations is a part of the Office of the Police Commissioner. Media Relations provides public information to local and national media outlets, conducts news conferences and interviews, and provides Department spokespersons to ensure that the public receives timely and accurate information about department-related activities, programs, services and personnel.\n* Internal Affairs investigates incidents of alleged police misconduct; reviews complaint investigations to ensure that investigations are thorough and complete; analyzes all complaint data; and proactively assists in the development of needed training modules.\n* The Boston Police Harbor Unit, led by the [[harbormaster]], patrols the harbor daily to ensure that both commercial and recreational use of the harbor and its islands is safe. The unit also enforces maritime codes and environmental regulations as they apply to these waters.\n* The Boston Police Rescue/Recovery Dive Team has 22 members and is overseen by a sergeant.  The team is made up of various members of the department working all across the city that may be activated, as needed.  The team responds to all underwater incidents in the city or in the 42 square miles of Boston Harbor. Also, the team is the primary investigative unit for any crimes that may occur on the Harbor Islands.\n* The Boston Police Licensing Division oversees civilian firearms licensing, Rule 400 Special Police Officer Licensing, and the Hackney Carriage Unit, which is responsible for regulating all taxis, sightseeing automobiles, horse and carriages, and [[pedicab]]s in the city of Boston.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cityofboston.gov/police/hackney/ |title=Hackney Carriage Unit &#124; Boston Police &#124; City of Boston |publisher=Cityofboston.gov |accessdate=2012-02-17}}</ref>\n* [[Boston Police Special Operations Unit]] is a specialized unit within the Boston Police Department responsible for combined duties involving [[highway patrol]] and traffic enforcement, crowd control, and special weapons and tactics ([[SWAT]]) services within the city. One unique feature of the unit is that the Special Operations Unit primarily relies on the use of [[Ford Crown Victoria Police Interceptor]]s and [[Harley-Davidson]]s in their daily patrols. The use of motorcycles allows the unit to perform routine traffic enforcement; accompany parades, crowds, and visiting dignitaries; and to quickly travel to situations wherein the unit's SWAT skills are requested. Specialized trucks and support vehicles are also used to transport equipment and officers when needed. The Canine Unit, Bomb Squad, Hazardous Materials Response Unit and the Truck Team are also under the Special Operations Division.\n* The high-tech desk provides inter-divisional technical support in areas such as IT (Information Technology), Digital Forensics support, and assists in investigations of [[cybercrime]].\n* [[Boston Police Gaelic Column of Pipes & Drums]]. Founded in 1992, The Boston Police Gaelic Column is an independent, non-profit organization consisting of Boston Police officers and law enforcement officers from the greater Boston area. The Gaelic Column is affiliated with the Boston Police Department but is funded entirely through the efforts of its members and supporters. They perform at Boston Police events, parades and other events throughout the Boston area.<ref name=\"gaeliccolumn\">{{cite web | url=http://www.bostonpolicegaeliccolumn.com | title=Boston Police Gaelic Column of Pipes and Drums | accessdate=February 23, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe Boston Police Department ran a cadet program, where 18- to 24-year-olds were assigned to a division where they performed administrative tasks such as writing reports and directing traffic. After two years as cadets, they were eligible to be candidates at the Police Academy. This program was cut in 2009, due to budget cuts and was brought back in 2015. New Police cadets first started on November 14, 2016.\n\n== Equipment ==\n{{expand section|date=December 2011}}\n\n=== Transportation ===\nThe Boston Police uses the following vehicles.\n* [[Ford Explorer#Ford_Police_Interceptor_Utility|Ford Police Interceptor SUV]] \u2013 Current issue patrol car.\n* [[Chevrolet Tahoe|Chevy Tahoe PPV]] \u2013 Current issue patrol car.\n* [[Ford Crown Victoria Police Interceptor]] \u2013 Mostly phased out as of July 2019. Occasionally seen on a detail, etc.\n* [[Ford F-Series|Ford F-250]] - Prisoner Transport Vehicle (paddy wagon)\n* [[Ford Expedition]]\n* [[Harley-Davidson]]\n* [[HMMWV]]\n\n=== Weapons ===\nBoston police officers may carry \"only weapons, magazines and ammunition authorized and issued by the Department\", which \"include, but are not limited to\":<ref name=sidearms>{{cite web|url=http://www.cityofboston.gov/images_documents/rule303_tcm3-9585.pdf |title=Boston Police Department Rules and Procedures: Rule 303, Use of Deadly Force |at=Section 9, page 5 |date=11 April 2003 |publisher=Boston Police Department |accessdate=2 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120526174456/http://www.cityofboston.gov/Images_Documents/rule303_tcm3-9585.pdf |archivedate=May 26, 2012 }}</ref>\n* [[Benelli M3|Benelli M3 SBS]] (12 gauge)\n* [[Bushmaster XM-15]] ([[.223 Remington]])\n* [[Glock#40 S&W|Glock Model 22]]<ref name=sidearms/> ([[.40 S&W]])\n* [[Glock#40 S&W|Glock Model 23]]<ref name=sidearms/> (.40 S&W)\n* [[Glock#40 S&W|Glock Model 27]]<ref name=sidearms/> (.40 S&W)\n* [[SIG Sauer GSR]] in [[.45 ACP]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sites.google.com/site/worldinventory/pw_massachusetts |title=Police Weapons in the USA: Massachusetts\n |date=11 April 2003 |publisher=Boston Police Department |quote=Sigarms .45 Caliber Pistol \u2013 8 Rounds |accessdate=2 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sigsauer.com/upFiles/Specifications-Comparison.pdf |title=Pistol Specifications |at=Chart 1 |publisher=[[SIG Sauer]] |accessdate=2 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111027111717/http://www.sigsauer.com/upFiles/Specifications-Comparison.pdf |archive-date=27 October 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Community policing ==\nIn the 1990s the police department resurrected an old idea, the Walk & Talk strategy. Police officers assigned to [[police car|patrol cars]] are required to walk a particular area for up to 45 minutes or longer per their tour of duty. The establishment of other initiatives like \"Same Cop Same Neighborhood\" and \"Safe Street Beat Teams\" have contributed widely to the continued success of community policing.{{Citation needed|date=October 2009}} These types of direct patrol were more widely expanded under the leadership of Police Commissioner Davis. Under his command Patrol Supervisors and police officers who were normally assigned to administrative duties were encouraged to perform a foot patrol. This type of patrol assignment is referred to as a Code 19.{{Citation needed|date=October 2009}}\n\n== Demographics ==\n\n;By gender\n* Male: 84%\n* Female: 16%\n\n;By race\n* White: 67%\n* African-American/Black: 23%\n* Hispanic: 8%\n* Asian: 2%<ref>[http://www.ojp.usdoj.gov/bjs/pub/pdf/lemas00.pdf Law Enforcement Management and Administrative Statistics, 2000: Data for Individual State and Local Agencies with 100 or More Officers] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090802114024/http://www.ojp.usdoj.gov/bjs/pub/pdf/lemas00.pdf |date=August 2, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==Fictional portrayals==\nThe Boston Police Department has been portrayed in several prominent motion pictures including ''[[Patriots Day (film)|Patriots Day]]'', ''[[Gone Baby Gone]]'', ''[[Mystic River (film)|Mystic River]]'', ''[[The Departed]]'', ''[[Edge of Darkness (2010 film)|Edge of Darkness]]'', ''[[Blown Away (1994 film)|Blown Away]]'', ''[[The Brinks Job]]'', ''[[That's My Boy (2012 film)|That's My Boy]]'', ''[[R.I.P.D.]]'', ''[[The Heat (film)|The Heat]]'', the second \"X-Men\" film ''[[X2 (film)]]'', ''[[What's The Worst That Could Happen?]]'', ''[[The Boondock Saints]]'', ''[[Surrogates (film)|Surrogates]]'', and ''[[The Town (2010 film)|The Town]]''. BPD is also featured in the television series ''[[Spenser: For Hire]]'', ''[[Rizzoli & Isles]]'', ''[[Leverage (TV series)|Leverage]]'', ''[[Crossing Jordan]]'', ''[[Fringe (TV series)|Fringe]]'', and the failed [[Katee Sackhoff]]/[[Goran Visnjic]] police show pilot ''[[Boston's Finest (TV series)|Boston's Finest]]''.\n\n===Fictional BPD districts===\nDue to filming on location in the Boston area, fake BPD cruisers have been marked with fictional districts to avoid confusion with real BPD cruisers.  They include:\n;District A-4\n* Featured in\n** ''[[Fringe (TV series)|Fringe]]''<ref>[http://justagwailo.com/2010/10/27/10689 Photo of fake BPD cruiser on ''Fringe'' set]</ref>\n;District A-8\n* Featured in\n** ''[[That's My Boy (2012 film)|That's My Boy]]'' outside a housing project\n** ''[[The Town (2010 film)|The Town]]'' throughout the film\n** ''[[R.I.P.D.]]'' during the raid where Nick is killed\n** ''[[Ted 2]]'' seen on the side of a police car\n** ''[[Patriots Day (film)|Patriots Day]]'' outside of David Henneberry's house on April 19\n;District D-6\n* Featured in\n** ''[[The Town (2010 film)|The Town]]'' outside [[Fenway Park]] during the final gunfight scene\n;District G-4\n* Featured in\n** ''[[Patriots Day (film)|Patriots Day]]''<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://scontent-lga3-1.xx.fbcdn.net/hphotos-xpf1/v/t1.0-0/p600x600/12998763_10209781161833755_5114774848379613929_n.jpg?oh=a7477d3e10ebe31d50afbe376725a128&oe=57AFD9E0# |title=Photo of fake BPD cruiser on ''Patriots Day'' set |access-date=2016-06-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160617165922/https://scontent-lga3-1.xx.fbcdn.net/hphotos-xpf1/v/t1.0-0/p600x600/12998763_10209781161833755_5114774848379613929_n.jpg?oh=a7477d3e10ebe31d50afbe376725a128&oe=57AFD9E0 |archive-date=2016-06-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n;District G-5\n* Featured in\n** ''[[Edge of Darkness (2010 film)|Edge of Darkness]]'' outside Craven's house as part of a protection detail\n** ''[[The Heat (2013 film)|The Heat]]'' Mullins works out of it, but it is somehow part of Area F rather than Area G\n;District G-8\n* Featured in\n** ''[[Leverage (TV series)|Leverage]]''<ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/ichad/4676497363/ Photo of fake BPD cruisers with Oregon license plates]</ref>\n;19th Precinct\n* Featured in\n** ''[[What's the Worst That Could Happen?]]'' Detective Tardio claims to be from it when first introducing himself\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[List of law enforcement agencies in Massachusetts]]\n* [[Boston Police Special Operations Unit]]\n* [[Boston Marathon bombing]]\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [[Francis Russell (author)|Francis Russell]]. [https://books.google.com/books?id=GOqa9-BWvmMC&printsec=frontcover ''A City in Terror: Calvin Coolidge and the 1919 Boston Police Strike''] (Boston: Beacon Press, 1975, {{ISBN|978-0-8070-5033-0}}).\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.bpdnews.com/ Boston Police Department blog, BPDNews.com]\n* [http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/articles/2006/04/13/police_union_to_fight_merger/ Boston Globe Article on the Merger]\n* The [http://www.library.neu.edu/archives/collect/findaids/m04find.htm Police News Collection, Scrapbooks, 1961-1968] are located in the Northeastern University Libraries, Archives and Special Collections Department, Boston, MA.\n* The [http://www.library.neu.edu/archives/collect/findaids/m129find.htm Elmer V.H. Brooks papers, 1924-1998 (Bulk 1937-1968)] are located in the Northeastern University Libraries, Archives and Special Collections Department, Boston, MA.\n* [http://www.library.neu.edu/archives/collect/findaids/m124find.htm The Justice George Lewis Ruffin Society records, n.d., 1848-1853, 1885-1893, 1963-2005 (bulk 1984-2005)] are located in the Northeastern University Libraries, Archives and Special Collections Department, Boston, MA.\n* Boston Police Department Annual Reports since 1885 https://web.archive.org/web/20100613003654/http://bpl.org/online/govdocs/bpd_reports.htm\n{{Boston Police Department}}\n{{BostonMA}}\n\n[[Category:Boston Police Department| ]]\n[[Category:Government of Boston]]\n[[Category:Municipal police departments of Massachusetts]]\n", "name_user": "Izuko", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRanks:Adjust rank tables so the columns align properly", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boston_Police_Department"}
{"title_page": "Dafina Zeqiri", "text_new": "{{Short description|Albanian singer and songwriter}}\n{{about|the Kosovo-Albanian singer|the Kosovo-Albanian composer|Dafina Zeqiri (composer)}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=May 2014}}\n{{tone|date=October 2015}}\n}}\n{{Infobox musical artist \n| name             = Dafina Zeqiri\n| image            =\n| caption          =\n| alias            = Duffye\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       =\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1989|4|14}}\n| birth_place      = [[Varberg]], Sweden\n| origin           =\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Dance music|Dance]]|[[Pop music|Pop]]|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]}}<ref name=\"Biography\"/>\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Singer|songwriter}}\n| years_active     = 2008\u2013present\n| label            = Moneyz\n| associated_acts  =\n}}\n \n'''Dafina Zeqiri''' ({{IPA-sq|dafina zeci\u027ei}}; born 14 April 1989), known professionally as '''Dafina''', is a [[Kosovo]]-[[Swedes|Swedish]] rapper and songwriter.<ref name=\"Biography\">{{cite web |title=Dafina Zeqiri\u2013Biografia |url=https://www.teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri |website=teksteshqip.com |accessdate=9 February 2020 |language=Albanian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Dafina Zeqiri\u2013Bio |url=http://topawards.top-channel.tv/index.php/artist/dafina-zeqiri/ |website=topawards.top-channel.tv |accessdate=9 February 2020 |language=Albanian}}</ref> \n \n== Life and career ==\n\nDafina Zeqiri was born on 14 April 1989 into a [[Kosovo Albanians|Kosovo Albanian]] family in the city of [[Varberg]], [[Sweden]]. Zeqiri's father was distant to her and to her mother, and she quoted that they haven't had contacts for more than 23 years.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri/lajme_4822.php |title=Dafina: Kam 23 vite q\u00eb nuk flas me babin. |access-date=2013-09-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130819125511/http://www.teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri/lajme_4822.php |archive-date=2013-08-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref> During a TV show in [[Klan Kosova]], Dafina's father made a public speech asking her to forgive him, but Dafina never made any replies.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri/lajme_2802.php |title=Pas rr\u00ebfimit t\u00eb babait, tani \u00ebsht\u00eb rradha e motr\u00ebs. |access-date=2013-09-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016134626/http://teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri/lajme_2802.php |archive-date=2012-10-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2014, Zeqiri made a song with Ledri Vula, a Kosovar [[rapper]] from [[Pristina]], whom she dated. There were a lot of rumors regarding their relationship, but they finally confirmed it during an acceptance speech in Videofest where the couple kissed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri/lajme_1848.php |title=Ledri dhe dafina, \u00e7ift? |access-date=2013-09-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029193514/http://www.teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri/lajme_1848.php |archive-date=2013-10-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri/lajme_2173.php |title=E v\u00ebrteta e historis\u00eb me Ledrin. |access-date=2013-09-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029193512/http://www.teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri/lajme_2173.php |archive-date=2013-10-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref> They later broke up.\n\n=== 2007\u20142011 ===\n\nIn 2007, Dafina performed in Polifest Festival and is nominated for her song, \"Rrall\u00eb e P\u00ebrmall\u00eb,\" and eventually won the competition.\n\nIn 2008, Dafina she received a BOOM Award Nomination for her song \"Adios,\" and was awarded with the audience award. In the same year, she launched her first album titled \"Knock Down\". Shortly afterwards, in her continued participation in \"K\u00ebnga Magjike,\" she received the \"First Magic\" award with her song, \"Baterit\u00eb\".\n\nIn 2009, her fame grew after a dancing competition in \"Op Labi Party (New Year 2009)\" where Dafina won against the most popular singers in Kosovo due to her mesmerizing voice and dancing skills. The success continued with two collaborations with known singers Blero & F-Kay with the song \"La Vida Loca\" and Capital T & 2po2, \"Shum\u00eb Nalt\u00eb\". Both songs turned into hits of the summer. In May 2009, she won \"Best RNB\" in Top Fest 6 with the song \"Dua q\u00eb ta di,\" a song which was a great success.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri/lajme_1958.php |title=Dafina Zeqiri n\u00eb Top Fest |access-date=2013-09-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016134111/http://teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri/lajme_1958.php |archive-date=2012-10-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Then Duffy'e also made the a mix of the song with the acclaimed DJ-Zap. In August, she was declared as \"Female Superstar 2009\" in Teksteshqip.com. In September, she attended the Awards with the song \"Amazing Girl\" and won the audience award for the third time. During 2009, two of her clips were very successful: \"Shum\u00eb Larg\" (directed by Stamps Pictures) and \"Amazing Girl\" (Directed by Entermedia).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri/lajme_1103.php |title=Dafina nuk din t\u00eb ndalet |access-date=2013-09-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016134825/http://teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri/lajme_1103.php |archive-date=2012-10-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri/lajme_2306.php |title=E lumtur pas suksesit t\u00eb klipit t\u00eb ri |access-date=2013-09-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016134418/http://teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri/lajme_2306.php |archive-date=2012-10-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2010, Dafina sang live in RTK \"Oxygen.\" After this show, Dafina traveled to Australia to shoot the clip of the song in English, \"Rock This Club.\" The video clip of the song \"Amazing Girl\" by Dafina was the main winner of this year's edition of Music Videofest, sweeping away the award for best videospot, 'Best of All'. She was nominated in eight categories and won four of them.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri/lajme_1980.php |title=Duffye dominates in Videofest nominations!In a total she has 12 Videofest Awards. |access-date=2013-09-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016134533/http://teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri/lajme_1980.php |archive-date=2012-10-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2011, Dafina Zeqiri released her newest album and a clip around the same time. In her album, the song D&G was included, a song she has made with the famous Albanian rapper Getoar Selimi, better known as \"Geti\". She has already launched her clip \"Tonight,\" which is also included in the new album \"Just Me\".\nShe launched 2 new music videos \"Ve\u00e7 Ti\" (later translated in English as \"Your Love\")<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri/lajme_4651.php |title=Dafina Zeqiri: English version of \"Ve\u00e7 ti\" |access-date=2013-09-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130818035254/http://teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri/lajme_4651.php |archive-date=2013-08-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and \"Bloodah\" which were successful.\n\n=== 2017\u2013present ===\n\nIn March 2017, following several months spent in the [[United States]], the singer released \"Four Season\" as the lead single from her upcoming [[extended play]] ''King EP''.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=[[Koha Ditore|Koha]] |title=Dafina Zeqiri publikon klipin e \"Four Season\" |url=https://www.koha.net/showbiz/4552/dafina-zeqiri-publikon-klipin-e-four-season/ |website=koha.net |accessdate=23 February 2020 |language=Albanian |date=8 March 2017}}</ref> In October 2017, she premiered the second single of the aforementioned extended play \"Told Ya\" and reached number one in Albania.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=[[Bota Sot]] |title=Dafina Zeqiri publikon k\u00ebng\u00ebn \"Told Ya\" |url=https://www.botasot.info/mediale-vip-showbiz/768859/dafina-zeqiri-publikon-kengen-told-ya/ |website=botasot.info |accessdate=23 February 2020 |language=Albanian |date=4 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Artistry ==\n\nDafina has cited [[Aaliyah]], [[Ciara]] and [[Michael Jackson]] as her major musical influences.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dafina Zeqiri kujton yjet e muzik\u00ebs q\u00eb nd\u00ebrruan jet\u00eb |url=https://telegrafi.com/dafina-zeqiri-kujton-yjet-e-muzikes-qe-nderruan-jete-foto/ |website=telegrafi.com |accessdate=9 February 2020 |language=Albanian |date=29 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n{{Main|Dafina Zeqiri discography}}\n\n* ''Knock Down'' (2008)\n* ''Just Me'' (2011)\n* ''King EP'' (2017)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Facebook|dafinamusic}}\n*{{Instagram|dafina.zeqiri}}\n*{{Twitter|Dafina_Zeqiri}} \n*[https://www.youtube.com/user/DafinaOfficial Dafina Zeqiri] on [[YouTube]]\n \n{{Albanian music}}\n{{Balkan music}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zeqiri, Dafina}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Pristina]]\n[[Category:People from Varberg]]\n[[Category:Albanian pop singers]]\n[[Category:Albanian rhythm and blues singers]]\n[[Category:Kosovan singers]]\n[[Category:Albanian songwriters]] \n[[Category:Albanian female singers]]  \n[[Category:Swedish female singers]]\n[[Category:Swedish people of Albanian descent]]\n[[Category:21st-century Albanian singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Swedish musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Swedish singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century women singers]]\n[[Category:Kosovo Albanians]] \n[[Category:Kosovan people of Albanian descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Albanian singer and songwriter}}\n{{about|the Kosovo-Albanian singer|the Kosovo-Albanian composer|Dafina Zeqiri (composer)}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=May 2014}}\n{{tone|date=October 2015}}\n}}\n{{Infobox musical artist \n| name             = Dafina Zeqiri\n| image            =\n| caption          =\n| alias            = Duffye\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       =\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1989|4|14}}\n| birth_place      = [[Varberg]], Sweden\n| origin           =\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Dance music|Dance]]|[[Pop music|Pop]]|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]}}<ref name=\"Biography\"/>\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Singer|songwriter}}\n| years_active     = 2008\u2013present\n| label            = Moneyz\n| associated_acts  =\n}}\n \n'''Dafina Zeqiri''' ({{IPA-sq|dafina zeci\u027ei}}; born 14 April 1989), known professionally as '''Dafina''', is a [[Kosovo]]-[[Albanians|Albanian]] rapper and songwriter.<ref name=\"Biography\">{{cite web |title=Dafina Zeqiri\u2013Biografia |url=https://www.teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri |website=teksteshqip.com |accessdate=9 February 2020 |language=Albanian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Dafina Zeqiri\u2013Bio |url=http://topawards.top-channel.tv/index.php/artist/dafina-zeqiri/ |website=topawards.top-channel.tv |accessdate=9 February 2020 |language=Albanian}}</ref> \n \n== Life and career ==\n\nDafina Zeqiri was born on 14 April 1989 into a [[Kosovo Albanians|Kosovo Albanian]] family in the city of [[Varberg]], [[Sweden]]. Zeqiri's father was distant to her and to her mother, and she quoted that they haven't had contacts for more than 23 years.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri/lajme_4822.php |title=Dafina: Kam 23 vite q\u00eb nuk flas me babin. |access-date=2013-09-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130819125511/http://www.teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri/lajme_4822.php |archive-date=2013-08-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref> During a TV show in [[Klan Kosova]], Dafina's father made a public speech asking her to forgive him, but Dafina never made any replies.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri/lajme_2802.php |title=Pas rr\u00ebfimit t\u00eb babait, tani \u00ebsht\u00eb rradha e motr\u00ebs. |access-date=2013-09-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016134626/http://teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri/lajme_2802.php |archive-date=2012-10-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2014, Zeqiri made a song with Ledri Vula, a Kosovar [[rapper]] from [[Pristina]], whom she dated. There were a lot of rumors regarding their relationship, but they finally confirmed it during an acceptance speech in Videofest where the couple kissed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri/lajme_1848.php |title=Ledri dhe dafina, \u00e7ift? |access-date=2013-09-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029193514/http://www.teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri/lajme_1848.php |archive-date=2013-10-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri/lajme_2173.php |title=E v\u00ebrteta e historis\u00eb me Ledrin. |access-date=2013-09-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029193512/http://www.teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri/lajme_2173.php |archive-date=2013-10-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref> They later broke up.\n\n=== 2007\u20142011 ===\n\nIn 2007, Dafina performed in Polifest Festival and is nominated for her song, \"Rrall\u00eb e P\u00ebrmall\u00eb,\" and eventually won the competition.\n\nIn 2008, Dafina she received a BOOM Award Nomination for her song \"Adios,\" and was awarded with the audience award. In the same year, she launched her first album titled \"Knock Down\". Shortly afterwards, in her continued participation in \"K\u00ebnga Magjike,\" she received the \"First Magic\" award with her song, \"Baterit\u00eb\".\n\nIn 2009, her fame grew after a dancing competition in \"Op Labi Party (New Year 2009)\" where Dafina won against the most popular singers in Kosovo due to her mesmerizing voice and dancing skills. The success continued with two collaborations with known singers Blero & F-Kay with the song \"La Vida Loca\" and Capital T & 2po2, \"Shum\u00eb Nalt\u00eb\". Both songs turned into hits of the summer. In May 2009, she won \"Best RNB\" in Top Fest 6 with the song \"Dua q\u00eb ta di,\" a song which was a great success.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri/lajme_1958.php |title=Dafina Zeqiri n\u00eb Top Fest |access-date=2013-09-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016134111/http://teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri/lajme_1958.php |archive-date=2012-10-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Then Duffy'e also made the a mix of the song with the acclaimed DJ-Zap. In August, she was declared as \"Female Superstar 2009\" in Teksteshqip.com. In September, she attended the Awards with the song \"Amazing Girl\" and won the audience award for the third time. During 2009, two of her clips were very successful: \"Shum\u00eb Larg\" (directed by Stamps Pictures) and \"Amazing Girl\" (Directed by Entermedia).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri/lajme_1103.php |title=Dafina nuk din t\u00eb ndalet |access-date=2013-09-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016134825/http://teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri/lajme_1103.php |archive-date=2012-10-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri/lajme_2306.php |title=E lumtur pas suksesit t\u00eb klipit t\u00eb ri |access-date=2013-09-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016134418/http://teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri/lajme_2306.php |archive-date=2012-10-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2010, Dafina sang live in RTK \"Oxygen.\" After this show, Dafina traveled to Australia to shoot the clip of the song in English, \"Rock This Club.\" The video clip of the song \"Amazing Girl\" by Dafina was the main winner of this year's edition of Music Videofest, sweeping away the award for best videospot, 'Best of All'. She was nominated in eight categories and won four of them.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri/lajme_1980.php |title=Duffye dominates in Videofest nominations!In a total she has 12 Videofest Awards. |access-date=2013-09-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016134533/http://teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri/lajme_1980.php |archive-date=2012-10-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2011, Dafina Zeqiri released her newest album and a clip around the same time. In her album, the song D&G was included, a song she has made with the famous Albanian rapper Getoar Selimi, better known as \"Geti\". She has already launched her clip \"Tonight,\" which is also included in the new album \"Just Me\".\nShe launched 2 new music videos \"Ve\u00e7 Ti\" (later translated in English as \"Your Love\")<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri/lajme_4651.php |title=Dafina Zeqiri: English version of \"Ve\u00e7 ti\" |access-date=2013-09-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130818035254/http://teksteshqip.com/dafina-zeqiri/lajme_4651.php |archive-date=2013-08-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and \"Bloodah\" which were successful.\n\n=== 2017\u2013present ===\n\nIn March 2017, following several months spent in the [[United States]], the singer released \"Four Season\" as the lead single from her upcoming [[extended play]] ''King EP''.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=[[Koha Ditore|Koha]] |title=Dafina Zeqiri publikon klipin e \"Four Season\" |url=https://www.koha.net/showbiz/4552/dafina-zeqiri-publikon-klipin-e-four-season/ |website=koha.net |accessdate=23 February 2020 |language=Albanian |date=8 March 2017}}</ref> In October 2017, she premiered the second single of the aforementioned extended play \"Told Ya\" and reached number one in Albania.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=[[Bota Sot]] |title=Dafina Zeqiri publikon k\u00ebng\u00ebn \"Told Ya\" |url=https://www.botasot.info/mediale-vip-showbiz/768859/dafina-zeqiri-publikon-kengen-told-ya/ |website=botasot.info |accessdate=23 February 2020 |language=Albanian |date=4 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Artistry ==\n\nDafina has cited [[Aaliyah]], [[Ciara]] and [[Michael Jackson]] as her major musical influences.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dafina Zeqiri kujton yjet e muzik\u00ebs q\u00eb nd\u00ebrruan jet\u00eb |url=https://telegrafi.com/dafina-zeqiri-kujton-yjet-e-muzikes-qe-nderruan-jete-foto/ |website=telegrafi.com |accessdate=9 February 2020 |language=Albanian |date=29 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n{{Main|Dafina Zeqiri discography}}\n\n* ''Knock Down'' (2008)\n* ''Just Me'' (2011)\n* ''King EP'' (2017)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Facebook|dafinamusic}}\n*{{Instagram|dafina.zeqiri}}\n*{{Twitter|Dafina_Zeqiri}} \n*[https://www.youtube.com/user/DafinaOfficial Dafina Zeqiri] on [[YouTube]]\n \n{{Albanian music}}\n{{Balkan music}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zeqiri, Dafina}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Pristina]]\n[[Category:People from Varberg]]\n[[Category:Albanian pop singers]]\n[[Category:Albanian rhythm and blues singers]]\n[[Category:Kosovan singers]]\n[[Category:Albanian songwriters]] \n[[Category:Albanian female singers]]  \n[[Category:Swedish female singers]]\n[[Category:Swedish people of Albanian descent]]\n[[Category:21st-century Albanian singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Swedish musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Swedish singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century women singers]]\n[[Category:Kosovo Albanians]] \n[[Category:Kosovan people of Albanian descent]]\n", "name_user": "79.166.166.14", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dafina_Zeqiri"}
